'order'       => 4,
'location'    => ['lat' => 41.8961, 'lng' => 12.4790],
'description' => 'One of Rome\'s most atmospheric yet under-visited archaeological sites lies in the middle of a busy traffic intersection just south of the Pantheon: the Largo di Torre Argentina, an excavated complex of four Republican-era temples dating from the 4th to 2nd centuries BC, making them among the oldest surviving Roman religious structures anywhere in the world. The temples are below modern street level — an instant visual illustration of how deeply buried the ancient city is — and can be viewed from raised walkways around the perimeter or explored from within via a small museum opened in 2023. Their names are unknown: archaeologists refer to them as Temples A, B, C, and D, each representing a different deity — likely Feronia, Juturna, Fortuna Huiusce Diei, and possibly Lares Permarini. But what makes this site truly extraordinary is its association with one of the most dramatic events in all of human history: it was in the Curia of Pompey, a meeting hall attached to the theatre of Pompey whose remains are incorporated into the northeast corner of the complex, that a group of senators including Brutus and Cassius surrounded Julius Caesar on the Ides of March — the 15th of March — 44 BC, and stabbed him 23 times. Caesar collapsed at the foot of a statue of his old ally and enemy Pompey, which stood at the entrance to the Curia. Today the site is also home to a colony of several hundred cats, descendants of the feral cats that have inhabited the ruins for centuries and are under the care of the Torre Argentina Cat Sanctuary — the cats lounge in the sunshine on the same stones that witnessed the death of the man who changed the course of Western civilisation.',
'translations' => [
'es' => ['title' => 'Largo di Torre Argentina — donde cayó César', 'description' => 'Uno de los yacimientos arqueológicos más atmosféricos aunque menos visitados de Roma se encuentra en medio de un concurrido cruce de tráfico al sur del Panteón: el Largo di Torre Argentina, un complejo de cuatro templos de la época republicana que datan de los siglos IV al II a.C. Lo que hace extraordinario a este sitio es su vinculación con uno de los eventos más dramáticos de la historia humana: fue aquí donde un grupo de senadores rodeó a Julio César el 15 de marzo del 44 a.C. y lo apuñaló 23 veces. El sitio también alberga una colonia de cientos de gatos que sestean al sol sobre las mismas piedras que fueron testigo de la muerte del hombre que cambió el curso de la civilización occidental.'],
'fr' => ['title' => 'Le Largo di Torre Argentina — là où tomba César', 'description' => 'L\'un des sites archéologiques les plus atmosphériques mais les moins visités de Rome se trouve au milieu d\'un carrefour animé au sud du Panthéon : le Largo di Torre Argentina, un complexe de quatre temples de l\'époque républicaine datant des IVe-IIe siècles av. J.-C. Ce qui rend ce site vraiment extraordinaire, c\'est son lien avec l\'un des événements les plus dramatiques de toute l\'histoire humaine : c\'est ici qu\'un groupe de sénateurs cerna Jules César le 15 mars 44 av. J.-C. et le poignarda 23 fois. Le site abrite aussi une colonie de centaines de chats qui somnolent au soleil sur les mêmes pierres qui furent témoins de la mort de l\'homme qui changea le cours de la civilisation occidentale.'],
'de' => ['title' => 'Largo di Torre Argentina — wo Cäsar fiel', 'description' => 'Eine der atmosphärischsten, aber am wenigsten besuchten archäologischen Stätten Roms liegt mitten in einer belebten Kreuzung südlich des Pantheons: das Largo di Torre Argentina, ein Komplex aus vier republikanischen Tempeln aus dem 4. bis 2. Jahrhundert v. Chr. Was diesen Ort wirklich außergewöhnlich macht, ist seine Verbindung mit einem der dramatischsten Ereignisse der Menschheitsgeschichte: Hier umzingelten Senatoren Julius Cäsar am 15. März 44 v. Chr. und stachen 23 Mal auf ihn ein. Die Stätte beherbergt auch eine Kolonie von Hunderten von Katzen, die in der Sonne auf denselben Steinen dösen, die Zeuge des Todes des Mannes wurden, der den Lauf der westlichen Zivilisation veränderte.'],
'it' => ['title' => 'Largo di Torre Argentina — dove cadde Cesare', 'description' => 'Uno dei siti archeologici più suggestivi ma meno visitati di Roma si trova nel mezzo di un trafficato incrocio a sud del Pantheon: il Largo di Torre Argentina, un complesso di quattro templi dell\'epoca repubblicana risalenti al IV-II secolo a.C. Ciò che rende questo sito straordinario è la sua associazione con uno degli eventi più drammatici della storia umana: fu qui che un gruppo di senatori circondò Giulio Cesare il 15 marzo del 44 a.C. e lo pugnalò 23 volte. Il sito ospita anche una colonia di centinaia di gatti che sonnecchiano al sole sulle stesse pietre che furono testimoni della morte dell\'uomo che cambiò il corso della civiltà occidentale.'],
],
