[
'title'       => 'Borghese Gallery — Bernini\'s Masterpieces',
'order'       => 6,
'location'    => ['lat' => 41.9141, 'lng' => 12.4921],
'description' => 'The Galleria Borghese is the finest small museum in Rome and one of the great art experiences of the world — a perfectly proportioned 17th-century villa containing a collection of such breathtaking quality that many visitors describe their experience here as the most moving of their entire lives. Cardinal Scipione Borghese, nephew of Pope Paul V, was the most voracious and discerning art collector of his era, and between 1613 and 1633 he acquired, commissioned, and occasionally simply seized through papal authority a collection that rivals the greatest in the world. The ground floor sculpture rooms contain six works by Gian Lorenzo Bernini made in his twenties — an achievement of such precocious genius that they have no parallel in the entire history of art. The Apollo and Daphne (1622-25) shows the moment the nymph transforms into a laurel tree to escape the pursuing god: marble carved to such translucent thinness that it trembles like a leaf, Daphne\'s fingers sprouting into branches with a tactile immediacy that defies belief. The Rape of Proserpina (1621-22) shows Pluto\'s hand sinking into Proserpina\'s thigh — his fingers pressing into marble as if into flesh — while her tears, her struggling body, and her desperate expression convey a psychological complexity that no sculptor before or since has surpassed at this age. Entrance is strictly limited to 360 visitors per two-hour session; booking is essential and should be made at least two weeks in advance, often more. The villa is set within the beautiful Villa Borghese gardens — Rome\'s central park — and a walk through the grounds makes an ideal conclusion to the tour.',
