'description' => 'Begin at the Plaça de Sant Jaume, the political and symbolic heart of Catalonia, where the two great institutions of Catalan self-governance have faced each other across a broad open square for seven centuries. On the north side stands the Palau de la Generalitat, the seat of the Catalan regional government, first established in 1359 — making it one of the oldest constitutional governments in the world, predating even the English Parliament in its continuous democratic function. Its main façade, completed in the Renaissance style in the 16th century, conceals a Gothic interior with an extraordinary first-floor courtyard containing an orange tree garden and the famous Sant Jordi Chapel, open to the public on the Diada de Sant Jordi (23 April) and selected Sundays throughout the year. Opposite stands the Ajuntament, Barcelona\'s City Hall, a Gothic building whose original 14th-century façade faces the narrow Carrer de la Ciutat while the grander Neoclassical front faces the square — a reminder that the current piazza was only created by demolishing several medieval blocks in the 19th century. The square sits on the exact intersection of the two principal streets of the original Roman city of Barcino — the Decumanus Maximus (now Carrer de la Llibreteria) and the Cardo Maximus (Carrer del Call and Carrer dels Arcs) — meaning that Romans have been meeting, arguing, governing, and protesting on this exact spot for 2,100 years. On weekends, the square often fills with Catalan folk dancers performing the Sardana, the traditional circular dance that has become a symbol of Catalan cultural identity.',
