'location'    => ['lat' => 41.3821, 'lng' => 2.1754],
'description' => 'From the Plaça de Sant Jaume, turn west into what was, for four centuries, the most vibrant Jewish community in medieval Iberia: El Call, Barcelona\'s historic Jewish quarter. The name derives from the Hebrew word "kahal" meaning community or congregation, and this densely packed neighbourhood — its streets so narrow that neighbours could almost shake hands across them from their upper windows — was home to a Jewish community continuously from at least the 9th century until the catastrophic pogrom of 1391, when anti-Jewish riots swept across the Iberian Peninsula and the Jewish quarter of Barcelona was systematically destroyed, its inhabitants murdered, forcibly converted, or expelled. At its height in the 13th and 14th centuries, Barcelona\'s Jewish community numbered around 4,000 people — roughly a tenth of the city\'s total population — and produced some of the most important Jewish scholars of the medieval world, including Rabbi Solomon ben Aderet (the Rashba), whose rabbinical rulings are still consulted in Jewish legal scholarship today, and the cartographer Abraham Cresques, creator of the famous Catalan Atlas of 1375 — the most accurate map of the known world produced in the entire medieval period, now in the Bibliothèque nationale de France in Paris. The tiny street of Carrer de Marlet contains a small but poignant medieval Hebrew inscription on a stone — one of the very few physical traces of this world left in the city. The nearby Centre d\'Interpretació del Call, housed in a medieval building, tells the community\'s story with sensitivity and scholarship.',
