$tours[] = [
'title'       => 'Golden Age Amsterdam: Canals, Art & Freedom',
'description' => 'In the 17th century, Amsterdam was the richest, most powerful, and arguably the most free city on earth — a fact that is inscribed in every canal, every gabled merchant\'s house, and every painting in the Rijksmuseum. The Dutch Golden Age, roughly 1585-1720, saw Amsterdam transform from a modest fishing town into the centre of a global trading empire: the Dutch East India Company (VOC), based here, was the world\'s first multinational corporation and the first company to issue shares to the public, effectively inventing capitalism in the process. The city that capitalism built is today one of Europe\'s most beautiful and liveable capitals, its 165 canals and 1,500 bridges forming a UNESCO World Heritage Site of extraordinary elegance. This tour follows the great arc of Golden Age Amsterdam: from the Anne Frank House — a window onto the century when all that Golden Age freedom was systematically destroyed — through the philosophical heart of the Jewish Quarter, to the Rijksmuseum\'s treasury of Rembrandt, Vermeer, and Frans Hals, finishing in the city\'s most characterful neighbourhood, the Jordaan.',
