[
'title'       => 'Portuguese Synagogue & Jewish Historical Museum',
'order'       => 5,
'location'    => ['lat' => 52.3661, 'lng' => 4.9048],
'description' => 'Cross to the east side of the city to discover one of Amsterdam\'s most beautiful and moving historic buildings: the Portuguese Synagogue, completed in 1675 and still in active use today — making it one of the oldest continuously functioning synagogues in the world. The building was commissioned by the Sephardic Jewish community that had settled in Amsterdam from the 1590s onwards, refugees from the Inquisition who had been expelled from Spain in 1492 and subsequently from Portugal in 1497, spending nearly a century in various forms of exile before finding in Amsterdam a degree of religious tolerance — imperfect and conditional, but real — that existed almost nowhere else in contemporary Europe. The interior of the synagogue is of extraordinary beauty and power: a vast rectangular hall lit by 72 windows and over 1,000 candles held in four brass chandeliers, the wooden seating arranged around a central raised bimah (reading platform), the walls hung with simple oak panelling. The candles are still the only artificial light used for Shabbat and high holiday services, creating an effect of amber warmth that photographs cannot fully convey. Amsterdam\'s Jewish Quarter was devastated during the Second World War: before the German occupation in 1940, approximately 80,000 Jews lived in Amsterdam; by the war\'s end, around 60,000 — 75% — had been murdered in the camps. The nearby Jewish Historical Museum tells this history with great depth and sensitivity, tracing the community\'s 400-year story in the city from the Portuguese Sephardic refugees through the Holocaust and its aftermath.',
'translations' => [
