'description' => 'Begin at the Stephansdom — the Cathedral of Saint Stephen — which has dominated the Vienna skyline for 700 years and which Viennese people regard with a fierce civic pride that goes far beyond the merely religious. The cathedral stands at the exact centre of the city, its 137-metre south tower (the "Steffl" — Little Stephan — as Viennese affectionately call it) visible from almost every point in the old city and beyond. The building\'s history reaches back to the 12th century: the earliest church on the site was consecrated in 1147, and the current structure is essentially a Gothic rebuilding of the 14th and 15th centuries, retaining the Romanesque west façade and towers from the earlier church. The south tower, completed in 1433, was the tallest structure in the German-speaking world for over two centuries and remains one of the finest examples of Gothic stone masonry anywhere in existence. The cathedral\'s diagonally patterned roof, covered in 230,000 glazed tiles in chevron patterns of black and yellow that spell out the Habsburg double eagle on the south slope, is one of the most distinctive architectural details in all of Austria. The interior contains 18 altars and numerous extraordinary artworks, but the most remarkable sight is the late Gothic stone pulpit (1515) by Anton Pilgram, whose carved draperies and stone lace are executed with a virtuosity that seems to deny the hardness of the material. Below the cathedral, the catacombs contain the internal organs of 72 Habsburg rulers in copper urns — their hearts rest in the Augustinerkirche nearby, and their bodies in the Imperial Crypt of the Kapuzinerkirche.',
