'steps' => [
[
'title'       => 'Josefov — The Jewish Quarter & Franz Kafka',
'order'       => 1,
'location'    => ['lat' => 50.0901, 'lng' => 14.4177],
'description' => 'Begin in Josefov, Prague\'s historic Jewish Quarter, which takes its name from Emperor Joseph II of Austria, who issued the Edict of Toleration in 1781 granting Jews in the Habsburg Empire significantly expanded civil rights — a moment of relative liberation that the Jewish community of Prague marked by renaming their quarter in his honour. Jews had lived in Prague since at least the 10th century, and the Josefov ghetto, while often overcrowded and economically constrained, developed into one of the most important centres of Jewish learning and culture in all of Europe, producing figures of world historical significance including Rabbi Judah Loew ben Bezalel — the Maharal of Prague — who lived here from 1573 to 1609 and is the subject of the most famous Jewish legend of the medieval world: the story of the Golem, a being made of clay animated by Kabbalistic magic to protect the Jewish community from attack. The Maharal\'s grave in the Old Jewish Cemetery is one of the most visited sites in Prague. Franz Kafka was born at the edge of the ghetto in 1883, grew up in its shadows, and spent his entire life within a few hundred metres of his birthplace — never leaving Prague for more than brief holidays. His most important works — The Trial, The Castle, The Metamorphosis — use the physical and bureaucratic geography of Prague and the Habsburg Empire as the backdrop for investigations into alienation, guilt, and the individual\'s helplessness before impersonal institutional power. The Franz Kafka Museum on the Malá Strana side of the river is an excellent introduction to his life and work.',
'translations' => [
'es' => ['title' => 'Josefov — el barrio judío y Franz Kafka', 'description' => 'Comience en el Josefov, el histórico Barrio Judío de Praga, que toma su nombre del Emperador José II de Austria, quien en 1781 concedió derechos civiles expandidos a los judíos del Imperio de los Habsburgo. Los judíos habían vivido en Praga desde al menos el siglo X, y el gueto Josefov se desarrolló como uno de los más importantes centros de aprendizaje y cultura judía de Europa. El Rabino Judah Loew ben Bezalel — el Maharal de Praga — es el sujeto de la famosa leyenda del Gólem. Franz Kafka nació al borde del gueto en 1883 y pasó toda su vida allí, escribiendo obras como El Proceso, El Castillo y La Metamorfosis.'],
'fr' => ['title' => 'Josefov — le quartier juif et Franz Kafka', 'description' => 'Commencez à Josefov, le quartier juif historique de Prague, qui tient son nom de l\'Empereur Joseph II d\'Autriche, qui en 1781 accorda des droits civils étendus aux juifs de l\'Empire des Habsbourg. Les juifs vivaient à Prague depuis au moins le Xe siècle, et le ghetto de Josefov est devenu l\'un des plus importants centres d\'apprentissage et de culture juifs d\'Europe. Le rabbin Judah Loew ben Bezalel — le Maharal de Prague — est le sujet de la célèbre légende du Golem. Franz Kafka naquit aux abords du ghetto en 1883 et passa toute sa vie ici, écrivant Le Procès, Le Château et La Métamorphose.'],
'de' => ['title' => 'Josefov — das Jüdische Viertel & Franz Kafka', 'description' => 'Beginnen Sie im Josefov, Prags historischem Jüdischen Viertel, das seinen Namen von Kaiser Joseph II. von Österreich erhielt, der 1781 den Juden im Habsburgerreich erweiterte Bürgerrechte gewährte. Juden lebten in Prag seit mindestens dem 10. Jahrhundert, und das Josefov-Ghetto entwickelte sich zu einem der wichtigsten Zentren jüdischen Lernens und Kultur in Europa. Rabbi Judah Loew ben Bezalel — der Maharal von Prag — ist Gegenstand der berühmten Golem-Legende. Franz Kafka wurde 1883 am Rand des Ghettos geboren und verbrachte sein ganzes Leben dort, und schrieb Der Process, Das Schloss und Die Verwandlung.'],
'it' => ['title' => 'Josefov — il Quartiere Ebraico e Franz Kafka', 'description' => 'Iniziate a Josefov, lo storico Quartiere Ebraico di Praga, che prende il nome dall\'Imperatore Giuseppe II d\'Austria, che nel 1781 concesse ai Ebrei dell\'Impero asburgico diritti civili significativamente ampliati. Gli ebrei vivevano a Praga almeno dal X secolo, e il ghetto Josefov si sviluppò in uno dei più importanti centri di apprendimento e cultura ebraica d\'Europa. Il Rabbino Judah Loew ben Bezalel — il Maharal di Praga — è il soggetto della famosa leggenda del Golem. Franz Kafka nacque ai margini del ghetto nel 1883 e trascorse tutta la vita lì, scrivendo Il Processo, Il Castello e La Metamorfosi.'],
],
],
[
'title'       => 'Old Town Square & the Astronomical Clock',
'order'       => 2,
'location'    => ['lat' => 50.0871, 'lng' => 14.4213],
'description' => 'From Josefov, walk south to the Staroměstské náměstí — the Old Town Square — one of the most spectacular medieval public spaces in Europe and the historical centre of Prague for over 900 years. The square is ringed by an extraordinary collection of historic buildings representing eight centuries of architectural styles: the Gothic towers of the Týn Church dominate the eastern side, their sharp spires rising 80 metres above the square; the Baroque St. Nicholas Church fills the northwest corner; Renaissance and Baroque merchant\'s houses line the south side; and the Gothic Old Town Hall anchors the western wall. But the square\'s most famous feature is the Orloj — the Prague Astronomical Clock — mounted on the south face of the Old Town Hall tower and first installed in 1410, making it the world\'s third-oldest astronomical clock and the oldest still in operation. The clock displays not just the time but the positions of the sun and moon relative to the zodiac, the date, the phases of the moon, and the time according to three different medieval timekeeping systems — a mechanical model of the medieval universe in brass, copper, and carved stone. Every hour on the hour, a mechanical performance unfolds: a skeleton (representing Death) pulls a rope to toll the bell, the twelve apostles parade past two windows, a rooster crows, and a Turk, a Miser, and Vanity shake their heads in reluctance at time\'s passage. The crowds that gather to watch this spectacle on the hour are a medieval tourist attraction in themselves.',
'translations' => [
'es' => ['title' => 'Plaza de la Ciudad Vieja y el Reloj Astronómico', 'description' => 'Desde Josefov, camina hacia el sur hasta la Staroměstské náměstí — la Plaza de la Ciudad Vieja — uno de los espacios públicos medievales más espectaculares de Europa. La plaza está rodeada por una extraordinaria colección de edificios históricos que representan ocho siglos de estilos arquitectónicos. El Orloj — el Reloj Astronómico de Praga — montado en la cara sur del Ayuntamiento de la Ciudad Vieja, fue instalado por primera vez en 1410, siendo el reloj astronómico en funcionamiento continuo más antiguo del mundo. Cada hora en punto, se despliega una actuación mecánica: un esqueleto tira de una cuerda, los doce apóstoles desfilan y un gallo canta.'],
'fr' => ['title' => 'La Place de la Vieille Ville et l\'Horloge Astronomique', 'description' => 'De Josefov, marchez vers le sud jusqu\'à la Staroměstské náměstí — la Place de la Vieille Ville — l\'un des espaces publics médiévaux les plus spectaculaires d\'Europe. L\'Orloj — l\'Horloge Astronomique de Prague — monté sur la façade sud de l\'Hôtel de Ville de la Vieille Ville, fut installé pour la première fois en 1410, étant la plus ancienne horloge astronomique encore en fonctionnement au monde. Toutes les heures, un spectacle mécanique se déroule : un squelette sonne la cloche, les douze apôtres défilent et un coq chante.'],
'de' => ['title' => 'Altstädter Ring & die Astronomische Uhr', 'description' => 'Von Josefov gehen Sie südlich zum Staroměstské náměstí — dem Altstädter Ring — einem der spektakulärsten mittelalterlichen öffentlichen Plätze Europas. Die Orloj — die Prager Astronomische Uhr — an der Südseite des Altstädter Rathausturms angebracht, wurde erstmals 1410 installiert und ist die älteste noch in Betrieb befindliche astronomische Uhr der Welt. Jede volle Stunde entfaltet sich eine mechanische Darbietung: Ein Skelett zieht an einem Seil, die zwölf Apostel ziehen vorbei und ein Hahn kräht.'],
'it' => ['title' => 'Piazza della Città Vecchia e l\'Orologio Astronomico', 'description' => 'Da Josefov, camminate verso sud fino alla Staroměstské náměstí — la Piazza della Città Vecchia — uno degli spazi pubblici medievali più spettacolari d\'Europa. L\'Orloj — l\'Orologio Astronomico di Praga — montato sulla faccia sud del campanile del Municipio della Città Vecchia, fu installato per la prima volta nel 1410, essendo il più antico orologio astronomico ancora in funzione al mondo. Ogni ora in punto si svolge uno spettacolo meccanico: uno scheletro suona la campana, i dodici apostoli sfilano e un gallo canta.'],
],
],
[
'title'       => 'Charles Bridge — Prague\'s Open-Air Gallery',
'order'       => 3,
'location'    => ['lat' => 50.0865, 'lng' => 14.4114],
'description' => 'The Charles Bridge — Karlův most — is perhaps the single most atmospheric spot in Prague and one of the most dramatic bridge crossings in all of Europe. Built between 1357 and approximately 1402 under Emperor Charles IV and his son Wenceslaus IV, the bridge stretches 516 metres across the Vltava River on 16 massive Gothic arches of sandstone, connecting the Old Town on the east bank to the Malá Strana (Lesser Town) and the Prague Castle complex on the west bank. For over 400 years it was the only bridge crossing the Vltava at Prague, making it the most important and most contested structure in the city — scene of battles, executions, coronation processions, and the daily commerce of a great medieval capital. Between 1683 and 1714, a series of 30 Baroque statues were added to the bridge\'s parapets — saints, martyrs, and holy figures in theatrical poses, their stone cloaks and wings frozen in mid-gesture against the backdrop of the river and the castle rising beyond. The statues (the originals are now in the National Museum to protect them from pollution; the bridge carries high-quality replicas) were modelled on the Angel Bridge in Rome and are the finest concentration of Baroque sculpture in the open air anywhere in Central Europe. Cross the bridge from east to west in the early morning — before 7am, when the tourist crowds have not yet assembled — for an experience that has not fundamentally changed since the 17th century: the castle above, the mist on the river, the statues emerging from the gloom.',
'translations' => [
'es' => ['title' => 'Puente de Carlos — la galería al aire libre de Praga', 'description' => 'El Puente de Carlos — Karlův most — es quizá el lugar más atmosférico de Praga y uno de los cruces de puente más dramáticos de Europa. Construido entre 1357 y aproximadamente 1402, el puente se extiende 516 metros sobre el río Moldava en 16 macizos arcos góticos de arenisca. Entre 1683 y 1714, se añadió una serie de 30 estatuas barrocas a los parapetos del puente — santos, mártires y figuras sagradas en poses teatrales. Cruce el puente de este a oeste en la mañana temprana — antes de las 7am — para una experiencia que no ha cambiado fundamentalmente desde el siglo XVII: el castillo arriba, la niebla sobre el río, las estatuas surgiendo de la penumbra.'],
'fr' => ['title' => 'Le Pont Charles — la galerie en plein air de Prague', 'description' => 'Le Pont Charles — Karlův most — est peut-être le lieu le plus atmosphérique de Prague et l\'une des traversées de pont les plus dramatiques d\'Europe. Construit entre 1357 et environ 1402, le pont s\'étend sur 516 mètres au-dessus de la Vltava sur 16 massives arches gothiques en grès. Entre 1683 et 1714, une série de 30 statues baroques furent ajoutées aux parapets du pont — saints, martyrs et figures sacrées dans des poses théâtrales. Traversez le pont d\'est en ouest tôt le matin — avant 7h — pour une expérience inchangée depuis le XVIIe siècle : le château au-dessus, la brume sur la rivière, les statues émergeant de la pénombre.'],
'de' => ['title' => 'Karlsbrücke — Prags Freiluftgalerie', 'description' => 'Die Karlsbrücke — Karlův most — ist vielleicht der atmosphärischste Ort in Prag und eine der dramatischsten Brückenquerungen in ganz Europa. Zwischen 1357 und etwa 1402 erbaut, erstreckt sich die Brücke 516 Meter über die Moldau auf 16 massiven gotischen Sandsteinbögen. Zwischen 1683 und 1714 wurde eine Reihe von 30 Barockstatuen auf den Brüstungen der Brücke hinzugefügt — Heilige, Märtyrer und heilige Figuren in theatralischen Posen. Überqueren Sie die Brücke früh morgens — vor 7 Uhr — für ein Erlebnis, das sich seit dem 17. Jahrhundert nicht grundlegend verändert hat.'],
'it' => ['title' => 'Ponte Carlo — la galleria all\'aperto di Praga', 'description' => 'Il Ponte Carlo — Karlův most — è forse il posto più suggestivo di Praga e uno dei più drammatici attraversamenti di ponte in Europa. Costruito tra il 1357 e circa il 1402, il ponte si estende per 516 metri sul fiume Moldava su 16 massicce arcate gotiche in arenaria. Tra il 1683 e il 1714, una serie di 30 statue barocche fu aggiunta ai parapetti del ponte — santi, martiri e figure sacre in pose teatrali. Attraversate il ponte da est a ovest di primo mattino — prima delle 7 — per un\'esperienza rimasta sostanzialmente immutata dal XVII secolo.'],
],
],
[
'title'       => 'Prague Castle — The Largest Castle Complex in the World',
'order'       => 4,
'location'    => ['lat' => 50.0901, 'lng' => 14.4000],
'description' => 'Climb the hill west of the Charles Bridge to reach the Prague Castle complex — a sprawling royal and ecclesiastical enclosure covering 70,000 square metres (7 hectares) that has served as the seat of Czech kings, Holy Roman Emperors, and presidents of the Czech Republic for over 1,100 years, making it the largest castle complex in the world by area. The complex is essentially a small town within the city: it contains three courtyards, St. Vitus Cathedral, the Old Royal Palace, St. George\'s Basilica, the Golden Lane, and numerous galleries, gardens, and historic buildings spanning 12 centuries of continuous construction. St. Vitus Cathedral, whose construction began in 1344 under Charles IV and was only completed in 1929 — nearly 600 years later — is the spiritual heart of the Czech nation, housing the tomb of Saint Wenceslas (the "Good King Wenceslas" of the Christmas carol, a real 10th-century Bohemian duke murdered by his brother), the crown jewels of Bohemia, and extraordinary stained glass windows including one designed by Alphonse Mucha in 1931 that glows with Art Nouveau intensity in the morning light. The Golden Lane — a row of tiny, colourful medieval cottages built into the castle walls in the 16th century for castle guards and later for goldsmiths (hence the name) — is one of the most charming streets in Prague; Franz Kafka lived briefly at number 22 in 1916-17. The views from the castle ramparts across the red rooftops of Malá Strana and the Vltava to the Old Town and beyond are definitive and unmissable.',
'translations' => [
'es' => ['title' => 'Castillo de Praga — el mayor complejo de castillos del mundo', 'description' => 'Suba la colina al oeste del Puente de Carlos para llegar al Castillo de Praga — un extenso recinto real y eclesiástico que cubre 70.000 metros cuadrados y que ha servido como sede de reyes checos y emperadores del Sacro Imperio Romano durante más de 1.100 años, lo que lo convierte en el mayor complejo de castillos del mundo por área. La Catedral de San Vito, cuya construcción comenzó en 1344 y solo se completó en 1929, es el corazón espiritual de la nación checa. El Callejón Dorado, una hilera de pequeñas cabañas coloridas del siglo XVI, es una de las calles más encantadoras de Praga; Franz Kafka vivió brevemente en el número 22 en 1916-17.'],
'fr' => ['title' => 'Le Château de Prague — le plus grand complexe de châteaux au monde', 'description' => 'Montez la colline à l\'ouest du Pont Charles pour atteindre le Château de Prague — un vaste enclos royal et ecclésiastique couvrant 70 000 mètres carrés qui a servi de siège aux rois tchèques et aux empereurs du Saint-Empire Romain Germanique pendant plus de 1 100 ans, ce qui en fait le plus grand complexe de châteaux au monde. La Cathédrale Saint-Guy, dont la construction a commencé en 1344 et ne s\'est achevée qu\'en 1929, est le cœur spirituel de la nation tchèque. La Ruelle d\'Or, une rangée de petites maisons colorées du XVIe siècle, est l\'une des rues les plus charmantes de Prague ; Franz Kafka y vécut brièvement au numéro 22 en 1916-17.'],
'de' => ['title' => 'Prager Burg — der größte Burgkomplex der Welt', 'description' => 'Erklimmen Sie den Hügel westlich der Karlsbrücke, um zum Prager Burgkomplex zu gelangen — einem weitläufigen königlichen und kirchlichen Gehege mit 70.000 Quadratmetern, das über 1.100 Jahre lang als Sitz tschechischer Könige und Kaiser des Heiligen Römischen Reiches gedient hat und damit der flächenmäßig größte Burgkomplex der Welt ist. Der Veitsdom, dessen Bau 1344 begann und erst 1929 abgeschlossen wurde, ist das spirituelle Herz der tschechischen Nation. Die Goldene Gasse, eine Reihe kleiner bunter mittelalterlicher Häuschen aus dem 16. Jahrhundert, ist eine der charmantesten Straßen Prags; Franz Kafka lebte kurzzeitig an Nummer 22 in 1916-17.'],
'it' => ['title' => 'Castello di Praga — il più grande complesso di castelli al mondo', 'description' => 'Salite la collina a ovest del Ponte Carlo per raggiungere il complesso del Castello di Praga — un vasto recinto reale ed ecclesiastico che copre 70.000 metri quadrati e che ha servito come sede dei re boemi e degli imperatori del Sacro Romano Impero per oltre 1.100 anni, rendendolo il più grande complesso di castelli al mondo per area. La Cattedrale di San Vito, la cui costruzione iniziò nel 1344 e fu completata solo nel 1929, è il cuore spirituale della nazione ceca. Il Vicolo d\'Oro, una fila di piccole colorate case medievali del XVI secolo, è una delle strade più affascinanti di Praga; Franz Kafka vi abitò brevemente al numero 22 nel 1916-17.'],
],
],
[
'title'       => 'U Fleků — Brewing Since 1499',
'order'       => 5,
'location'    => ['lat' => 50.0796, 'lng' => 14.4199],
'description' => 'Conclude your Prague tour with a visit to U Fleků, a brewery-restaurant that has been continuously producing and serving beer since 1499 — making it one of the oldest functioning breweries in the world and a monument to Czech brewing culture that is as historically significant in its own way as the castle or the cathedral. The Czech Republic produces more beer per capita than any other country in the world, and Czech brewing culture is taken with a seriousness that approaches reverence: the Pilsner style — the world\'s most widely consumed beer style, accounting for the vast majority of all beer drunk globally — was invented in the Bohemian city of Plzeň (Pilsen) in 1842, when the town council hired the Bavarian brewer Josef Groll to rescue their failing beer production and he created, apparently by accident, the world\'s first clear golden lager, a revelation after centuries of dark, cloudy ales. U Fleků brews only one beer: a dark, 13° Märzen-style lager of deep mahogany colour, served in half-litre ceramic mugs in a series of medieval hall-like rooms decorated with carved wood, painted murals, and over 500 years of accumulated atmosphere. The brewery produces only about 6,000 hectolitres per year — tiny by industrial standards — all consumed on the premises. The traditional Czech way to drink here is to sit, order your first beer (a second will appear automatically unless you place a beer mat over the glass), eat svíčková (beef sirloin in cream sauce) or smažený sýr (fried cheese), and allow the evening to organise itself.',
'translations' => [
