'description' => 'Lisbon is the westernmost capital city in continental Europe and, in many ways, the most melancholy and most romantic. Built on seven hills above the Tagus estuary — the point from which Vasco da Gama departed in 1497 to round the Cape of Good Hope and reach India, inaugurating the Age of Global Trade — it is a city of extraordinary light, extraordinary beauty, and the most beautiful sadness in European music: fado, the art form born in Lisbon\'s oldest neighbourhoods, in which the Portuguese concept of saudade — a longing for something lost, something that may never have existed — finds its most perfect expression. The 1755 earthquake, one of the most powerful ever recorded in Europe, destroyed most of the city in minutes and killed between 30,000 and 40,000 people; the reconstruction, directed by the Marquis of Pombal under the orders of King José I, created the elegant Pombaline grid of the Baixa district — one of the first planned city centres in modern history, built on earthquake-resistant foundations. This tour explores the city\'s contradictions: imperial glory and colonial guilt, seismic destruction and architectural renewal, northern melancholy and southern warmth.',
