$tours[] = [
'title'       => 'Imperial Budapest: Baths, Ruin Bars & the Danube Bend',
'description' => 'Budapest is one of Europe\'s most dramatically beautiful capital cities — a place where a 19th-century imperial metropolis sits astride a river of mythic importance, where Ottoman thermal baths bubble beneath neo-Gothic parliament buildings, and where the raw creativity of post-communist counterculture has transformed derelict Jewish Quarter tenements into some of the most inventive bars and cultural spaces on the continent. The city is technically two cities — Buda on the hilly western bank and Pest on the flat eastern bank — unified in 1873 into a single capital whose ambition was to rival Vienna as the co-capital of the Austro-Hungarian Empire. The result is a city of magnificent contradictions: Habsburg grandeur and Stalinist brutalism, medieval castle ramparts and modernist ruin bars, the ancient thermal waters of Roman Aquincum and the contemporary energy of a city that has rediscovered its confidence after decades of communist suppression. The entire Danube bank — both sides — is a UNESCO World Heritage Site, and the view from the Fisherman\'s Bastion across the river to the illuminated Parliament at night is one of the great urban spectacles on earth.',
'duration'    => 210,
'country'     => 'Hungary',
'city'        => 'Budapest',
'location'    => ['lat' => 47.4979, 'lng' => 19.0402],
'steps'       => [
[
'title'       => 'Buda Castle & the Castle District',
'order'       => 1,
'location'    => ['lat' => 47.4960, 'lng' => 19.0399],
'description' => 'Begin on the Buda side of the river at the Castle District — the Várnegyed — a UNESCO-listed plateau of medieval streets, baroque palaces, Gothic churches, and royal history perched 60 metres above the Danube on Castle Hill. The fortified settlement here dates to the 13th century, when King Béla IV ordered a royal castle built after the Mongol invasion of 1241 laid waste to the undefended lowland city — a catastrophe that killed half the population of medieval Hungary and fundamentally reshaped how Hungarians built and defended their cities. The Royal Palace that dominates the southern end of the hill today is largely an 18th and 19th-century reconstruction: the original medieval palace was destroyed during the Ottoman siege of 1686, rebuilt under Habsburg rule, badly damaged in the Second World War, and reconstructed again under communist rule in a somewhat austere neo-Baroque style. Today it houses the Hungarian National Gallery and the Budapest History Museum, both worth visiting. The true character of the Castle District is found not in the palace but in the medieval street plan between the Fisherman\'s Bastion and the Matthias Church: Holy Trinity Square, Uri utca, Táncsics utca, and the network of Gothic sedilia — stone window seats carved into doorways for the use of the urban poor waiting to petition their noble hosts — that survive from the 14th and 15th centuries. The Matthias Church (Mátyás-templom), originally built in 1015 and reconstructed in Gothic style in the 14th century, is one of the most beautiful churches in Hungary, its diamond-patterned polychrome tile roof visible from across the river.',
],
[
'title'       => 'Fisherman\'s Bastion — Budapest\'s Most Iconic Viewpoint',
'order'       => 2,
'location'    => ['lat' => 47.5018, 'lng' => 19.0344],
'description' => 'Immediately adjacent to the Matthias Church, the Fisherman\'s Bastion — Halászbástya — is one of Budapest\'s most photographed landmarks and offers what is widely regarded as the finest panoramic view of the Danube, Pest, and the Hungarian Parliament Building in the entire city. Despite its medieval appearance, the bastion is entirely a 19th-century construction, built between 1895 and 1902 to designs by Frigyes Schulek as part of the massive urban beautification programme that accompanied Budapest\'s millennial celebrations in 1896 — the thousandth anniversary of the Magyar conquest of the Carpathian Basin. The name refers to the fishermen\'s guild of the medieval city, whose members were historically responsible for defending this section of the castle walls. The structure is a fairy-tale ensemble of seven neo-Romanesque towers representing the seven Magyar tribes that founded Hungary, connected by terraced walkways, staircases, and arcaded galleries that frame the river and city views like a series of stage sets. The view from the upper terrace encompasses the entire sweep of the Danube below, the Chain Bridge connecting Buda and Pest, the massive neo-Gothic Parliament Building on the Pest bank — one of the largest parliament buildings in the world at 268 metres long — and on clear days, the hills of Transylvania to the east. The equestrian statue of King Stephen I (István), Hungary\'s first Christian king and founder of the Hungarian state, stands prominently on the main terrace. Come at dawn or at dusk when the golden light transforms the view into something approaching the sublime.',
],
[
'title'       => 'Széchenyi Thermal Bath — 1,000 Years of Hot Springs',
'order'       => 3,
'location'    => ['lat' => 47.5186, 'lng' => 19.0817],
'description' => 'Cross the Chain Bridge to Pest and take the metro to City Park (Városliget) to reach the Széchenyi Thermal Bath — the largest medicinal bath complex in Europe and one of the most extraordinary public institutions in Budapest, a city that sits atop one of the world\'s richest concentrations of geothermal spring water. Budapest has 118 natural thermal springs within the city boundaries, producing 70 million litres of mineral-rich water daily at temperatures between 21°C and 78°C — a geological legacy of the tectonic fault line that runs beneath the city and has been exploited for bathing since the Roman settlement of Aquincum in the 1st century AD. The Széchenyi baths were built between 1909 and 1913 in a magnificent neo-Baroque palace style — all golden stone, ornate domes, statuary, and decorative tilework — set within the City Park at the eastern end of Andrássy Avenue. The complex contains 15 indoor pools, 3 outdoor pools, and 10 saunas and steam rooms, all fed by two geothermal springs producing water at 74°C that is cooled to bathing temperature before use. The outdoor pools — particularly the famous central pool where chess players set their boards on floating wooden platforms in all weathers, a tradition documented since the 1930s — are open year-round, and the sight of steam rising from the turquoise water against a winter snowfall is one of Budapest\'s most memorable experiences. Bathing culture in Budapest is not a tourist activity but a genuine civic institution: locals come here for physical therapy, relaxation, and social interaction with the same regularity that others might go to a gym or a café. Allow two hours minimum; three is better.',
],
[
'title'       => 'The Jewish Quarter & Ruin Bars',
'order'       => 4,
'location'    => ['lat' => 47.4988, 'lng' => 19.0625],
'description' => 'Budapest\'s VII district — the historic Jewish Quarter — is one of the most compelling and historically layered urban neighbourhoods in Central Europe, a place where the grandeur of the largest synagogue in Europe sits alongside the ruins of the Budapest Ghetto, and where the devastating losses of the Holocaust have been followed — improbably, movingly — by a remarkable cultural and creative renaissance that has made this one of the most inventive districts in any European city. The Great Synagogue on Dohány Street — the Dohány Street Synagogue — was completed in 1859 to designs by Ludwig Förster in a Moorish Revival style, its twin Byzantine-Ottoman domes and ornate façade creating a building of astonishing architectural ambition. With seating for 3,000 worshippers, it remains the largest synagogue in Europe and the second largest in the world. In the courtyard behind, the Tree of Life sculpture by Imre Varga commemorates the 550,000 Hungarian Jews murdered in the Holocaust — in 1944, Hungary deported Jews to Auschwitz faster than any other country in occupied Europe, most of them in just eight weeks between May and July. The ruin bar phenomenon that has transformed the district since the mid-2000s began when young entrepreneurs began squatting in the bombed-out and communist-era-derelict buildings and courtyards of the old ghetto, filling them with mismatched furniture, art installations, and cheap drinks. Szimpla Kert — Simple Garden — opened in 2004 in a gutted courtyard on Kazinczy Street and effectively invented the genre; it now receives over a million visitors per year and hosts a Sunday farmers\' market. The bars that followed — Fogasház, Instant, Ellátó, Doboz — each developed their own character in a neighbourhood that feels genuinely alive with creative energy.',
],
[
'title'       => 'Hungarian Parliament Building — Neo-Gothic on the Danube',
'order'       => 5,
'location'    => ['lat' => 47.5072, 'lng' => 19.0454],
'description' => 'The Hungarian Parliament Building — Országház — on the Pest bank of the Danube is one of the great architectural spectacles of Europe and the most recognisable symbol of Budapest, its neo-Gothic silhouette of 96 towers, spires, and pinnacles reflected in the Danube creating an image that has graced a thousand postcards and yet never fails to astonish on first sight. Built between 1885 and 1904 to designs by Imre Steindl, the Parliament is the third-largest parliament building in the world at 268 metres long, 123 metres wide, and 96 metres tall — the height, like the year of completion, deliberately chosen to reference 896, the year of the Magyar conquest of the Carpathian Basin and the founding of the Hungarian state. The building contains 691 rooms, 29 staircases, 10 courtyards, and 40 kilometres of corridors — and is covered inside and out with an extraordinary programme of decorative arts: Hungarian historical paintings, tapestries, sculptures, and ornamental stonework of the highest quality. The central dome is 96 metres high, supported by 16 pillars around which stand statues of Hungarian rulers from Árpád, the leader of the Magyar conquest, to Ferdinand I. Beneath the dome, the Holy Crown of Hungary — one of the most symbolically potent objects in Central European history, the crown used to crown Hungarian kings since the 11th century (and hidden by Hungarian diplomats in Fort Knox from 1945 until its return in 1978) — is displayed under permanent guard in the Hall of the Crown. Guided tours of the interior are available daily; tickets should be booked in advance, particularly in summer.',
],
[
'title'       => 'Andrássy Avenue & the House of Terror',
'order'       => 6,
'location'    => ['lat' => 47.5012, 'lng' => 19.0631],
'description' => 'Stretching northeast from the inner city to City Park, Andrássy Avenue is Budapest\'s grandest boulevard, a UNESCO World Heritage Site in its own right, and a street of multiple identities that embodies the turbulent history of the 20th century with unusual directness. Laid out between 1872 and 1885, the avenue was conceived as Budapest\'s answer to Paris\'s Champs-Élysées — a 2.3-kilometre promenade of neo-Renaissance palaces, French-influenced townhouses, luxury shops, and theatre buildings culminating in the grand neoclassical colonnades of Heroes\' Square and City Park beyond. The Hungarian State Opera House, opened in 1884 at number 22 and widely considered one of the most beautiful opera houses in the world, was designed by Miklós Ybl with a neo-Renaissance façade and an auditorium of breathtaking gilt-and-velvet opulence. Emperor Franz Joseph I attended the opening, reportedly insisting that Vienna\'s opera house (which Ybl had been inspired by) should be declared the finer of the two — a diplomatic necessity he enforced by reducing Budapest\'s state subsidy. Number 60 Andrássy Avenue is one of the most chilling addresses in the city and in Central European history: this handsome neo-Renaissance building served first as the headquarters of the fascist Arrow Cross party (1944-45), who used its basement as a torture and execution facility during the brief but catastrophic period of their rule; and then as the headquarters of the AVH, Hungary\'s communist secret police (1945-1956), who continued using the same basement for the same purposes. Today it houses the House of Terror museum — a powerful and harrowing memorial to the victims of both totalitarian regimes, designed with artistic and architectural boldness that has made it one of the most discussed history museums in Europe.',
],
],
];

// ============================================================
// TOUR 2 — FLORENCE: Renaissance Masterpieces & Medici Power
// ============================================================
$tours[] = [
'title'       => 'Renaissance Florence: Medici Power, Art & the Birth of the Modern World',
'description' => 'Florence — Firenze — is the city where the modern world was born. In the 15th century, in this compact wool-trading town on the Arno River in Tuscany, a small group of artists, architects, philosophers, and their extraordinarily wealthy patrons — the Medici banking dynasty above all — reinvented the entire Western conception of art, architecture, literature, philosophy, and science. The Renaissance — the rebirth of classical learning and a new confidence in human reason and human beauty — began here, and its effects are still being felt in every aspect of contemporary life. The city that produced Brunelleschi, Donatello, Botticelli, Leonardo da Vinci, and Michelangelo within a single century is today one of the most concentrated collections of artistic genius in the world: the Uffizi Gallery alone contains more great paintings per square metre than anywhere else on earth. Yet Florence is not a museum — it is a living city of 370,000 people, with neighbourhood markets, artisan workshops, trattorias serving dishes unchanged since the 15th century, and a civic pride that has sustained this concentration of beauty through seven centuries of political upheaval, flood, war, and the relentless pressure of mass tourism.',
'duration'    => 210,
'country'     => 'Italy',
'city'        => 'Florence',
'location'    => ['lat' => 43.7696, 'lng' => 11.2558],
'steps'       => [
[
'title'       => 'The Duomo — Brunelleschi\'s Dome',
'order'       => 1,
'location'    => ['lat' => 43.7731, 'lng' => 11.2560],
'description' => 'The Cattedrale di Santa Maria del Fiore — the Duomo — is Florence\'s most recognisable landmark and the building that, more than any other, signifies the ambition, ingenuity, and artistic confidence of the Renaissance. The cathedral was begun in 1296 to designs by Arnolfo di Cambio in the Italian Gothic style, and the nave, campanile (bell tower designed by Giotto), and baptistery were all largely complete by the mid-14th century — yet there was a problem. A 42-metre octagonal hole had been left at the crossing where the dome was to be built, but no one knew how to build a dome large enough to span it. The solution eluded engineers and architects for over 50 years until Filippo Brunelleschi, a goldsmith-turned-architect with no formal training in masonry, proposed an audacious solution in 1418: he would build not one dome but two, one inside the other, using a system of herringbone brickwork and self-supporting rings that eliminated the need for the traditional wooden centring that would have required stripping Tuscany of its forests. The dome, completed in 1436 after 16 years of construction, is 45 metres in diameter at the base and 91 metres tall — the largest masonry dome in the world, which it remains today, 600 years later, never surpassed. Climbing the 463 steps between the two dome shells to the lantern reveals how the construction works from the inside — the herringbone brickwork visible at close range, the ribs curving upward, and at the top, a vertiginous view of Florence that Brunelleschi himself never saw from this vantage point. The adjacent Baptistery of San Giovanni, with Lorenzo Ghiberti\'s famous bronze "Gates of Paradise" (originals now in the Museo dell\'Opera del Duomo), is one of the oldest buildings in Florence and was venerated as the city\'s most ancient monument even in Dante\'s time.',
],
[
'title'       => 'Uffizi Gallery — The Greatest Collection of Renaissance Art',
'order'       => 2,
'location'    => ['lat' => 43.7677, 'lng' => 11.2553],
'description' => 'The Galleria degli Uffizi — the Office Gallery, named after the administrative offices that occupied the building from its construction in the 1560s under Giorgio Vasari — is the most important collection of Italian Renaissance painting in the world and one of the oldest and most visited museums in existence, attracting nearly 4 million visitors per year. The collection was assembled over two centuries by the Medici family — the Florentine banking dynasty whose patronage of art and scholarship made the Renaissance possible — and donated to the city of Florence in perpetuity in 1743 by the last Medici heir, Anna Maria Luisa, on the condition that it "never be removed from Florence." The density of masterworks in the Uffizi is unlike anything else: Room 10-14 alone contains Botticelli\'s Birth of Venus and Primavera — the two most famous paintings of the Italian Renaissance — alongside his Adoration of the Magi, in which the Medici family pose as the Three Wise Men with what appears to be genuine self-portraiture by the young Botticelli himself. Leonardo da Vinci\'s Annunciation hangs nearby, painted when he was approximately 20 years old and already demonstrating the atmospheric perspective and psychological subtlety that would make him the most famous artist in history. Caravaggio\'s Medusa, Michelangelo\'s Holy Family (the Doni Tondo), Raphael\'s portraits of Leo X and Julius II, Titian\'s Venus of Urbino — the museum is a succession of rooms each of which would be the centrepiece of any other institution in the world. Book timed-entry tickets in advance; in high summer, same-day entry without pre-booking is essentially impossible.',
],
[
'title'       => 'Piazza della Signoria & the Palazzo Vecchio',
'order'       => 3,
'location'    => ['lat' => 43.7697, 'lng' => 11.2559],
'description' => 'Just steps from the Uffizi, the Piazza della Signoria has been the political heart of Florence for seven centuries — an L-shaped open-air museum of sculpture and architecture that serves simultaneously as town square, civic monument, and theatre of power. The dominant building is the Palazzo Vecchio — the Old Palace — a massive 14th-century fortified city hall whose crenellated battlements and soaring 94-metre bell tower have defined the Florence skyline since 1322. The building\'s name reflects its demotion: it was the Palazzo della Signoria (the palace of the governing council) until the Medici Grand Dukes moved in during the 16th century, then became the Palazzo Vecchio when Duke Cosimo I moved to the Pitti Palace across the Arno and the old palace was given to his wife Eleanor of Toledo. Today it functions as Florence\'s city hall and a museum; the interior contains frescoes by Vasari, sculptures by Michelangelo and Donatello (copies; originals in the Bargello), and the extraordinary Sala del Cinquecento — a vast meeting room whose walls were originally to be decorated by Leonardo da Vinci and Michelangelo in direct competition, a contest that was never completed but whose preparations profoundly influenced both artists. The square itself is an open-air gallery: Cellini\'s bronze Perseus with the Head of Medusa in the Loggia dei Lanzi is one of the supreme achievements of Renaissance metalwork; Giambologna\'s Rape of the Sabine Women is a marble tour-de-force designed to be viewed from every angle simultaneously; and a copy of Michelangelo\'s David stands where the original stood until 1873 (now in the Accademia), marking the spot from which Florence\'s first citizen once surveyed the city his creator wanted him to defend.',
],
[
'title'       => 'Galleria dell\'Accademia — Michelangelo\'s David',
'order'       => 4,
'location'    => ['lat' => 43.7767, 'lng' => 11.2588],
'description' => 'A ten-minute walk north of the Duomo, the Galleria dell\'Accademia houses one of the most famous sculptures in the world and a work whose physical presence, even after centuries of reproduction, continues to stun visitors into silence: Michelangelo\'s David, carved between 1501 and 1504 from a single block of Carrara marble that had been quarried 40 years earlier and abandoned as impossible to work — damaged, with an awkward shape, far too narrow for the standing figure it was meant to produce. Michelangelo, then 26 years old, accepted the commission and within three years had produced the most celebrated male nude in Western art, a figure 5.17 metres tall (17 feet) whose anatomical precision, psychological intensity, and sheer physical beauty have never been surpassed in marble. The subject is the Biblical hero David, but Michelangelo\'s interpretation is entirely original: rather than showing the victorious moment after the battle as Donatello and Verrocchio had done before him, he shows David before the encounter with Goliath, in the instant of decision — his body tense with barely contained energy, his expression combining absolute concentration with a trace of the awareness that what he is about to do may be beyond even his formidable capability. The veins on the back of his right hand, the torsion of the neck, the oversized hands and head (deliberately exaggerated to correct for the viewing angle from below) — every detail rewards sustained study. The hall in which the David stands was specifically designed by Giuseppe Martini in 1882 with a skylit barrel-vaulted tribune to display it: the figure is visible from the entrance, 60 metres away, and the walk toward it is one of the most dramatically conceived museum experiences in the world.',
],
[
'title'       => 'Oltrarno & the Pitti Palace — The Medici\'s Private World',
'order'       => 5,
'location'    => ['lat' => 43.7651, 'lng' => 11.2499],
'description' => 'Cross the Arno River via the famous Ponte Vecchio — the Old Bridge, the only bridge in Florence not destroyed by the retreating Germans in 1944, spared apparently on the personal orders of Hitler, who wanted to preserve the view — into the Oltrarno, the neighbourhood "beyond the Arno" that is in many respects the most authentically Florentine part of the city. The Oltrarno has always had a slightly independent, artisan character: its streets are full of traditional craft workshops — leather workers, restorers, gilders, frame makers, bookbinders — operating in studios that have sometimes been in the same family for generations. The Palazzo Pitti, the enormous Renaissance palace that dominates the southern bank, was originally built in 1458 for the merchant Luca Pitti as a deliberately larger version of the Medici palace — an act of competitive ostentation that backfired when Pitti went bankrupt and the Medici bought the palace they had inadvertently inspired. Duke Cosimo I moved the Medici court here in 1550, and it remained the principal residence of the Florentine and later Italian rulers until 1919. Today the palace complex contains five separate museums: the Palatine Gallery holds the Medici\'s private art collection (Raphael, Titian, Rubens, and Caravaggio in extraordinary concentration in rooms still decorated as they were when the paintings were hung); the Royal Apartments show the 19th-century state rooms; and the Boboli Gardens behind — a 45,000 square metre terraced Renaissance garden of fountains, grottoes, statues, and cypress allées climbing the hill above the palace — offer the finest view of Florence from the south.',
],
[
'title'       => 'Mercato Centrale & San Lorenzo — The Medici\'s Parish',
'order'       => 6,
'location'    => ['lat' => 43.7754, 'lng' => 11.2537],
'description' => 'Complete your Florentine experience in the neighbourhood of San Lorenzo, the Medici\'s own parish church and the commercial heart of the city, centred on the extraordinary Mercato Centrale — Florence\'s covered food market, housed in a spectacular two-storey cast-iron and glass structure built in 1874 by the engineer Giuseppe Mengoni (who also designed Milan\'s Galleria Vittorio Emanuele II). The ground floor is a working wholesale and retail food market of the finest Tuscan produce: whole prosciutti hanging in rows, wheels of Parmigiano, fresh pasta in every conceivable shape, Chianina beef, truffles, aged balsamic, local wines, and the extraordinary variety of Florentine street food — in particular the lampredotto sandwich (tripe slow-cooked in broth, served in a bun dipped in the cooking liquid with a spoonful of green sauce) that is the quintessential Florentine working-class lunch, eaten at market stalls since the medieval period. The Basilica di San Lorenzo beside the market was the Medici family parish church, rebuilt by Brunelleschi from 1419 in the purest early Renaissance style — a masterwork of classical proportion and harmonious geometry that influenced Italian church architecture for the next two centuries. The Old Sacristy (designed by Brunelleschi) and New Sacristy (designed by Michelangelo, who carved the extraordinary tomb sculptures of Lorenzo and Giuliano de\' Medici) attached to the basilica contain some of the most significant Renaissance sculpture outside the Accademia. The adjacent Biblioteca Medicea Laurenziana, also by Michelangelo, is the greatest repository of humanist manuscripts in the world and one of the most innovative pieces of architecture the Renaissance produced.',
],
],
];

// ============================================================
// TOUR 3 — VENICE: Serenissima — Canals, Masks & Dying Beauty
// ============================================================
$tours[] = [
'title'       => 'La Serenissima: Canals, Palaces & the Art of a Vanishing City',
'description' => 'Venice is the most improbable city ever built and the most beautiful. Constructed on 118 small islands in the middle of a shallow lagoon on the northeast coast of Italy, connected by 400 bridges over 150 canals, with no roads and no cars — only boats, gondolas, and the feet of its visitors — Venice defies every rational principle of urban planning and exists in triumphant, beautiful, increasingly fragile contradiction of them all. For a thousand years, the Republic of Venice — La Serenissima, "The Most Serene" — was the most powerful trading state in the Mediterranean world, controlling the spice routes between Asia and Europe and accumulating a wealth that was channelled into the most extraordinary concentration of Gothic, Byzantine, and Renaissance architecture anywhere in the world. Today the city is slowly sinking — literally, by approximately 1-2 mm per year — while the tides of climate change and the weight of mass tourism threaten its very existence. Walking its calli (alleys) and crossing its campi (squares) in the early morning, before the day-trippers arrive, is one of the most extraordinary experiences available in Europe: a city that seems to exist outside time, its beauty unchanged from the canvases of Canaletto and Bellini, its silence broken only by the lap of water and the bells of San Marco.',
'duration'    => 210,
'country'     => 'Italy',
'city'        => 'Venice',
'location'    => ['lat' => 45.4408, 'lng' => 12.3155],
'steps'       => [
[
'title'       => 'Piazza San Marco — The Drawing Room of Europe',
'order'       => 1,
'location'    => ['lat' => 45.4341, 'lng' => 12.3388],
'description' => 'Napoleon, who occupied Venice in 1797 and dissolved the thousand-year-old Republic of Venice in a single afternoon, called the Piazza San Marco "the finest drawing room in Europe" — a description that has never been improved upon. The only space in Venice officially designated a piazza (all others are called campo or campiello), San Marco is ringed on three sides by the Procuratie buildings — the 16th-century administrative offices of the Republic — and opens on the fourth onto the extraordinary façade of the Basilica di San Marco and, beyond, the Lagoon. The Basilica itself is unlike any other church in Europe: a Byzantine-Oriental confection of five domes, golden mosaics, porphyry columns, and looted marble accumulated over a thousand years of trading empire, begun in 829 to house the bones of St. Mark, stolen by Venetian merchants from Alexandria (the mosaic in the left portal shows how this was done: the relics were packed in barrels of salt pork to deter Muslim customs inspectors). The interior is covered in over 8,000 square metres of gold mosaic depicting the entire Christian narrative, glittering with a warmth and intensity that the Byzantine craftsmen who created it designed to simulate the light of paradise. Climb to the museum terrace for close views of the original bronze horses (the replicas outside are the ones Napoleon took to Paris and was forced to return in 1815) and a panoramic view of the piazza below. The Campanile — the bell tower — collapsed without warning on 14 July 1902, killing only a cat, and was rebuilt brick-by-brick as an exact replica, reopening in 1912.',
],
[
'title'       => 'Doge\'s Palace — Power and the Abyss',
'order'       => 2,
'location'    => ['lat' => 45.4337, 'lng' => 12.3401],
'description' => 'Attached to the Basilica and overlooking the Lagoon, the Doge\'s Palace — Palazzo Ducale — was for a thousand years the centre of power of the Venetian Republic and is one of the most architecturally extraordinary buildings in Europe: a Gothic palace in pink Veronese marble and white Istrian stone, its arcaded lower stories supporting a solid upper wall decorated with a geometric pattern of inlaid marble lozenges, the whole thing appearing to defy gravity by placing the heaviest part on top of the lightest — a deliberate inversion of structural logic that is the building\'s most discussed formal characteristic. The palace was the residence of the Doge (the elected head of the Venetian state, in theory a lifetime appointment but in practice closely controlled by the patrician oligarchy of the Great Council), the seat of government, and the location of the law courts and state prison. The interior is a succession of rooms of escalating grandeur and escalating art: the Sala del Maggior Consiglio — the Great Council Hall — is one of the largest rooms in the world at 54 by 25 metres, its walls and ceiling entirely covered in paintings by Tintoretto and Veronese, the ceiling featuring Veronese\'s apotheosis of Venice (Apotheosis of Venice) in the central panel, the walls lined with portraits of every Doge from the 9th century to the fall of the Republic — except one, Marino Falier, executed for treason in 1355 and represented by a painted black cloth where his portrait should be. The tour continues across the Bridge of Sighs — the covered stone bridge connecting the palace to the New Prison, through which condemned prisoners passed — arguably the most romanticised architectural element in the most romanticised city in the world.',
],
[
'title'       => 'The Grand Canal by Vaporetto',
'order'       => 3,
'location'    => ['lat' => 45.4380, 'lng' => 12.3191],
'description' => 'Board the Number 1 vaporetto (the slow water bus) at the San Marco stop and ride its entire length — approximately 45 minutes — to the Santa Lucia train station at the northern end of the Grand Canal, the S-shaped waterway that divides Venice in two and constitutes the city\'s main artery and its most spectacular street. The Grand Canal is approximately 3.8 kilometres long and between 30 and 70 metres wide, and its banks are lined from end to end with an unbroken sequence of Gothic, Byzantine, Romanesque, Renaissance, and Baroque palaces representing the accumulated investment of 700 years of Venetian mercantile wealth. Over 170 palazzi line the canal, each built by a different merchant family competing to demonstrate their wealth and status through architectural ambition. The most important are: the Ca\' d\'Oro (House of Gold, 1430), the finest Venetian Gothic palace in existence, named for the gold leaf that once covered its façade; the Ca\' Rezzonico, a Baroque palazzo now housing the Museum of 18th-century Venice, where Robert Browning died in 1889; the Ca\' Foscari, a late Gothic masterpiece now part of Venice University; the Palazzo Corner della Ca\' Grande, designed by Jacopo Sansovino in 1537, the grandest Renaissance palace on the canal; and the Ca\' Pesaro, a Baroque extravaganza now housing the Museum of Oriental Art and the International Gallery of Modern Art. At the southern end, the white marble church of Santa Maria della Salute, built as a votive offering for deliverance from the plague of 1630, frames the canal\'s entrance to the Lagoon with magnificent theatrical effect. The vaporetto is the cheapest and most spectacular art tour in Venice.',
],
[
'title'       => 'Gallerie dell\'Accademia — The Soul of Venetian Painting',
'order'       => 4,
'location'    => ['lat' => 45.4311, 'lng' => 12.3271],
'description' => 'The Gallerie dell\'Accademia contains the definitive collection of Venetian painting from the 14th to the 18th centuries, housed in a complex of former religious buildings on the south bank of the Grand Canal in the Dorsoduro district. Venetian painting is fundamentally different from Florentine or Roman painting: where the Tuscans emphasised drawing, line, and the representation of ideal form, the Venetians — working in a city whose light filtered through water and reflected off canals — developed an unparalleled mastery of colour, atmospheric effect, and the painting of rich textiles, flesh tones, and the quality of light at specific times of day. Giovanni Bellini\'s luminous altarpieces, in which Madonnas sit in landscapes suffused with the gold-and-amber light of the Venetian lagoon at sunset, established the tone. Giorgione — the most mysterious and influential painter of the early 16th century — developed it further in works like The Tempest, whose ambiguous subject (a soldier watches a nursing woman in a landscape as lightning strikes) has resisted interpretation for 500 years and seems to have no iconographic programme at all, just the mood of a moment captured in paint. Titian, the greatest colourist in Western painting, spent 70 active years transforming Venetian art and European painting with it. Tintoretto\'s enormous canvases fill rooms with swirling action, dramatic foreshortening, and a light that seems to come from within the paint. Paolo Veronese\'s Feast in the House of Levi — originally a Last Supper, renamed after the Inquisition objected to the inclusion of dwarves, buffoons, and Germans in the scene — is 13 metres wide and was once the largest painting in Venice.',
],
[
'title'       => 'Burano — The Island of Lace and Colour',
'order'       => 5,
'location'    => ['lat' => 45.4851, 'lng' => 12.4175],
'description' => 'Take the 40-minute vaporetto ride from the Fondamente Nove to the island of Burano — one of the most visually arresting places in the entire Venetian Lagoon and a place of startling, joyful beauty that offers complete relief from the crowds and grandeur of the main islands. Burano is a fishing village of approximately 2,500 inhabitants clustered along four narrow canals and famous throughout the world for two things: its tradition of handmade needle lace, which was the most valuable textile in 16th and 17th-century Europe (a single elaborate collar could cost the equivalent of a palace) and its painted houses, which are the most intensely and variously coloured buildings in Italy — every house a different shade of red, orange, pink, yellow, blue, green, and purple, the colours regulated by a local government system that assigns each family their permitted palette. The legend behind the colours is romantic if possibly apocryphal: fishermen painted their houses in bright contrasting colours so they could recognise them from the lagoon through the mist. The Scuola dei Merletti (Lace Museum) tells the history of Buranella lace with remarkable detail, including the story of how the industry died in the 18th century when Venetian trade declined and was revived in the late 19th century by a school established to support the island\'s impoverished widows. Genuine handmade Burano lace — distinguished from cheaper machine-made or imported imitations by its irregular texture and the presence of the artisan\'s card — is among the finest textile crafts in Europe; pieces can take months to produce and prices reflect this. The main canal and the campi behind it are lined with restaurants serving fresh lagoon seafood: crab, scallops, soft-shell crab (moleche, seasonal), and grilled fish of remarkable freshness and quality.',
],
],
];

// ============================================================
// TOUR 4 — DUBROVNIK: The Pearl of the Adriatic
// ============================================================
$tours[] = [
'title'       => 'Dubrovnik: The Pearl of the Adriatic — Walls, Sea & the Republic of Ragusa',
'description' => 'George Bernard Shaw famously wrote: "Those who seek paradise on Earth should come to Dubrovnik." It is one of the most quoted sentences in travel writing, and while hyperbole is the language of tourism, in this case the exaggeration is barely perceptible. Dubrovnik is one of the best-preserved medieval walled cities on earth, a compact marvel of Gothic, Renaissance, and Baroque architecture perched on a limestone promontory above the impossibly blue Adriatic Sea on the southern coast of Croatia, and its UNESCO-listed old town — entered through fortress gates, pedestrianised entirely, and enclosed within walls that took centuries to build and centuries of determined citizens to maintain — is a place of extraordinary beauty that has earned its reputation as Europe\'s finest city. For five centuries from the 14th to the early 19th century, Dubrovnik was the capital of the independent Republic of Ragusa — a small but fiercely independent city-state that used diplomacy, commercial cunning, and a comprehensive system of international trade agreements to remain free when surrounded by larger and more powerful states. The Republic was one of the first in the world to abolish the slave trade (1416), to establish a quarantine system (1377 — the world\'s first, invented here to control the Black Death), and to create a public health service (1431). Its decline began with the catastrophic earthquake of 1667, which killed a quarter of the population and destroyed much of the medieval fabric — the Baroque buildings that replaced the Gothic originals are what visitors see today.',
'duration'    => 180,
'country'     => 'Croatia',
'city'        => 'Dubrovnik',
'location'    => ['lat' => 42.6507, 'lng' => 18.0944],
'steps'       => [
[
'title'       => 'The City Walls — Walking Above the Adriatic',
'order'       => 1,
'location'    => ['lat' => 42.6416, 'lng' => 18.1060],
'description' => 'Begin with the experience that is, for most visitors, the defining memory of Dubrovnik: walking the complete circuit of the city walls. The walls were built and continuously strengthened between the 8th and 17th centuries, reaching their final form under the Republic of Ragusa, which invested vast sums in their construction as the primary guarantee of the city\'s independence. The complete circuit is approximately 1.9 kilometres and takes between 60 and 90 minutes at a comfortable pace, though most visitors take considerably longer due to the relentless photographic temptation of every corner. The walls vary in height from 4 to 6 metres and in width from 1.5 to 6 metres; they are reinforced by five fortresses, two corner towers, 14 square towers, three bastions, and two angle towers, as well as the great Minceta Tower at the highest northern point — designed by Michelozzo di Bartolomeo of Florence and completed by Juraj Dalmatinac in 1464. The views from the walls are remarkable in every direction: seaward, the walls plunge almost directly into the Adriatic, and looking down at the crystalline turquoise water with the red-tiled rooftops of the old town immediately below is an image of Mediterranean beauty that justifies every superlative. Inland, the walls reveal the old town\'s surprisingly dense and uniform urban fabric — the product of the rapid reconstruction after the 1667 earthquake, which was conducted to a uniform standard that accidentally produced the visual cohesion that makes the city so beautiful from above. Start early — by 9am the circuit becomes uncomfortably crowded in peak season.',
],
[
'title'       => 'Stradun — The Marble Main Street',
'order'       => 2,
'location'    => ['lat' => 42.6416, 'lng' => 18.1077],
'description' => 'The Stradun — also known as the Placa — is Dubrovnik\'s main thoroughfare and one of the most beautiful streets in Europe: a perfectly straight, 300-metre-long pedestrian promenade of polished limestone pavement that connects the Pile Gate in the west to the Bell Tower and the Clock Tower in the east, flanked on both sides by uniform Baroque buildings of honey-coloured stone built after the earthquake of 1667. The Stradun follows the line of a shallow canal that was filled in during the 12th century to create a more direct connection between the former island of Ragusa and the Slavic settlement on the mainland — the unification of the two communities that effectively created the city. The polished stone surface of the pavement — worn smooth over centuries by the passage of millions of feet, it is said the limestone glows in a particular way on moonlit nights — was relaid in 1991 after Serbian and Montenegrin forces shelled the old town during the Croatian War of Independence, damaging approximately two-thirds of the buildings within the walls. The shells that landed on the Stradun itself left their marks in the pavement; some have been left unrepaired as a memorial. Despite the darkness of that recent history, the Stradun today is exactly what it was designed to be: a place for the theatre of civic life, where residents and visitors mingle on café terraces, children chase each other across the marble, and the rhythm of daily life in a Mediterranean city continues as it has for seven centuries.',
],
[
'title'       => 'Fort Lovrijenac — The Rock of Freedom',
'order'       => 3,
'location'    => ['lat' => 42.6407, 'lng' => 18.1035],
'description' => 'Outside the western Pile Gate, on a sheer rocky promontory rising 37 metres above the sea, the fortress of Lovrijenac is one of the most dramatically situated military structures in Europe and a building of immense symbolic importance for the Republic of Ragusa. Built on the orders of the Ragusan Senate in the early 11th century — according to tradition, in response to a Venetian attempt to build a fortress on the same rock in order to control the harbour — the fort was constructed in just three months, an astonishing speed that reflects both the engineering capability of the Republic and the urgency of the political situation. An inscription above the main gate reads "NON BENE PRO TOTO LIBERTAS VENDITUR AURO" — "Freedom cannot be sold for all the gold in the world" — a statement that encapsulates the Ragusan philosophy of independence that sustained the Republic for five centuries. The walls facing the sea are 12 metres thick; the walls facing the city are only 60 centimetres thick — a deliberate design choice to ensure that if the fort were ever captured by an enemy, it would provide no defensive advantage against the city itself. For Game of Thrones viewers, the fort is one of the locations used for the Red Keep of King\'s Landing, alongside the old town walls and the adjacent Bokar Fortress. The Croatian Summer Festival (July-August) uses the fort\'s upper terrace as an outdoor theatre; performances of Hamlet here — with the inscription visible and the Adriatic stretching to the horizon — are among the most atmospheric theatrical experiences in Europe.',
],
[
'title'       => 'Rector\'s Palace & the Ragusan Republic',
'order'       => 4,
'location'    => ['lat' => 42.6411, 'lng' => 18.1107],
'description' => 'The Rector\'s Palace on Pred Dvorom — the main square east of the Stradun — was the centre of government of the Republic of Ragusa for five centuries and one of the finest examples of Gothic-Renaissance architectural fusion in the eastern Adriatic. The palace is named for the Rector — Knez in Croatian — who served as the head of state of the Republic for one month at a time. The restriction to a single month was deliberate and brilliantly conceived: the Rector was elected by the Great Council from among the patrician class, moved into the palace at the start of his term, and was required to remain inside it — leaving only for state ceremonies — for his entire month of office. He was also prohibited from ever serving again. This system was designed to prevent any individual from accumulating power, influence, or the connections that might enable a coup: by rotating the highest office monthly between different patrician families and ensuring no one could hold it twice, the Republic guarded its republican constitution against the tyrants that consumed most other Italian city-states. The result was a remarkably stable and surprisingly democratic (for its time) system of government that lasted from 1358 to 1808. The palace itself, begun in the 14th century and rebuilt several times after fires and an explosion of the gunpowder stored in the basement (1463), combines Gothic arches in the loggia with Renaissance capitals and Baroque features added in later restorations. Today it houses the Cultural History Museum of Dubrovnik, with exhibits on the Republic\'s extraordinary diplomatic and commercial history.',
],
[
'title'       => 'Lokrum Island — The Enchanted Garden',
'order'       => 5,
'location'    => ['lat' => 42.6264, 'lng' => 18.1229],
'description' => 'Take the short ferry (15 minutes) from the old harbour to Lokrum — the small island 600 metres offshore that has been the wildest, most romantic, and most cursed spot in the Dubrovnik area for the better part of a thousand years. The island has been continuously associated with remarkable stories: Richard the Lionheart reportedly washed ashore here after a shipwreck in 1192 and, grateful for his survival, offered to fund the construction of a church on the island — the Ragusans diplomatically accepted his gratitude but redirected the funds to the Dubrovnik Cathedral, arguing it would be of more benefit to the city. A Benedictine monastery was established in the 11th century, suppressed by Napoleon\'s forces in 1798, and its monks supposedly placed a curse on anyone who attempted to take private ownership of the island — a curse that has been fulfilled with remarkable consistency: subsequent private owners include Archduke Maximilian of Austria (later Emperor Maximilian I of Mexico, executed in 1867), who built the formal gardens and cloisters still visible today; and the Duchess of Leuchtenberg, who sold it to the city after several inexplicable deaths. Today the island is a nature reserve of extraordinary beauty: endemic peacocks wander the paths freely, subtropical vegetation creates a lush green canopy, a saltwater lake in the centre (the Dead Sea) is warm enough for swimming in summer, and the rocky sea coast offers some of the clearest swimming water in the entire Adriatic. The Game of Thrones Iron Throne replica installed in the monastery cloister is the most visited artefact in Croatia.',
],
],
];

// ============================================================
// TOUR 5 — KRAKOW: Royal City, Jewish Heritage & Auschwitz
// ============================================================
$tours[] = [
'title'       => 'Royal Krakow: Dragons, Jewish Heritage & the Weight of History',
'description' => 'Krakow is Poland\'s most beautiful city and the one that most completely preserves the layered identity of a Central European metropolis that has passed through medieval splendour, imperial grandeur, Nazi occupation, and communist suppression to emerge as one of the most visited and most culturally vibrant cities on the continent. Unlike Warsaw — which was systematically destroyed by the Nazis in 1944 and rebuilt from scratch after the war — Krakow was spared deliberate destruction, its architectural heritage preserved through a combination of historical circumstance and the efforts of its citizens. The result is a city whose medieval market square, Gothic cathedral, Renaissance castle, and historic Jewish quarter form a coherent urban landscape of extraordinary beauty that feels genuinely lived-in rather than museified. Krakow was Poland\'s royal capital from the 11th to the late 16th century, the coronation site of Polish kings, and the home of the Jagiellonian University — the second oldest university in Central Europe, founded in 1364, where Nicolaus Copernicus studied astronomy in the 1490s. The city\'s Jewish Quarter of Kazimierz, devastated in the Holocaust and later used as a film set for Schindler\'s List (Steven Spielberg filmed here in 1992), has since transformed into one of the most creative and culturally interesting neighbourhoods in Poland. Any visit to Krakow must also reckon with its proximity to Auschwitz-Birkenau — the largest Nazi extermination camp, where approximately 1.1 million people were murdered between 1940 and 1945 — 60 kilometres to the west. A visit there is not a tourist experience but a moral obligation.',
'duration'    => 210,
'country'     => 'Poland',
'city'        => 'Krakow',
'location'    => ['lat' => 50.0647, 'lng' => 19.9450],
'steps'       => [
[
'title'       => 'Rynek Główny — Europe\'s Largest Medieval Market Square',
'order'       => 1,
'location'    => ['lat' => 50.0619, 'lng' => 19.9368],
'description' => 'Begin at the Rynek Główny — the Grand Market Square — the largest medieval town square in Europe at 200 by 200 metres and the vibrant heart of Krakow for over 700 years. The square was laid out in 1257 following the Mongol destruction of the earlier city, its dimensions reflecting the new town plan drawn up by Krakow\'s founder Prince Bolesław V the Chaste, and it has served continuously as the commercial, ceremonial, and social centre of the city ever since. The centrepiece of the square is the Cloth Hall — the Sukiennice — a Renaissance arcade built over the site of the original medieval trading rows, rebuilt after a fire in 1555 in a beautiful Renaissance style with an elegant arcade of arches on the ground floor (still occupied by souvenir and handicraft sellers as they have been for five centuries) and the National Museum\'s Gallery of 19th-Century Polish Art on the upper floor. The Town Hall Tower — all that remains of the medieval town hall demolished in the early 19th century — stands at the western end and can be climbed for panoramic views. The Church of St. Mary (Kościół Mariacki) on the northeast corner is one of the finest examples of Gothic brick architecture in Central Europe; its main altar, carved by the German sculptor Veit Stoss between 1477 and 1489, is the largest Gothic altarpiece in the world at 13 metres high and 11 metres wide, its 200 carved figures capturing the death and assumption of the Virgin with extraordinary emotional intensity. Every hour on the hour, a bugler plays a traditional melody — the Hejnał Mariacki — from the taller of the church\'s two towers, always stopping abruptly mid-phrase to commemorate the legendary 13th-century bugler who was shot through the throat by a Mongol arrow while sounding the alarm.',
],
[
'title'       => 'Wawel Castle & Cathedral — Poland\'s National Sanctuary',
