'location'    => ['lat' => 50.0543, 'lng' => 19.9355],
'description' => 'A fifteen-minute walk south of the market square, the Wawel Hill rises above the Vistula River bearing Poland\'s most sacred buildings: the Royal Castle and the Cathedral, together constituting the most important complex of historic monuments in Poland and a site of profound national identity that survived partition, occupation, and communism as a symbol of Polish continuity. The Castle was the residence of Polish kings from the 11th century until King Sigismund III Vasa moved the capital to Warsaw in 1596, and it remains the spiritual capital of Poland in a way that transcends mere geography. The current Renaissance palace, built for King Sigismund I the Old from 1502 onwards by Italian architects brought specially from Florence, is one of the finest Renaissance buildings in Central Europe — its three-storey arcaded courtyard, completed around 1536, is directly influenced by Italian models but adapted to the Polish climate and tradition with a warmth and human scale that makes it one of the most welcoming Renaissance spaces anywhere. The castle contains the Polish Crown Jewels (the coronation sword — Szczerbiec — is the only surviving piece of the original regalia) and the State Rooms with their extraordinary collection of Flemish tapestries commissioned by Sigismund II Augustus in the 1550s — 136 Brussels tapestries survive from the original 356, the largest collection of 16th-century Flemish tapestry in the world. The Cathedral, built between the 11th and 14th centuries, is the coronation church of Polish kings and the burial place of almost every Polish monarch, national hero, and poet of the last eight centuries: Casimir III the Great, Jadwiga of Poland, Jan III Sobieski, Tadeusz Kościuszko, Adam Mickiewicz, and Pope John Paul II (before his beatification) are among the remarkable company interred in the crypts.',
],
[
'title'       => 'Kazimierz — The Jewish Quarter',
'order'       => 3,
'location'    => ['lat' => 50.0525, 'lng' => 19.9470],
'description' => 'A twenty-minute walk southeast of Wawel Castle, the district of Kazimierz — established as a separate town by King Casimir III the Great in 1335 and incorporated into Krakow only in 1800 — was for over five centuries one of the most important Jewish communities in Europe, a centre of Jewish learning, publishing, and commerce whose synagogues, yeshivas, and market squares attracted scholars and merchants from across the continent. At its height in the late 19th century, the Jewish population of Kazimierz numbered around 30,000 — roughly 30% of Krakow\'s total population. By 1945, virtually all of them were dead. The Nazi occupation established the Krakow Ghetto not in Kazimierz but in the Podgórze district across the river, using the process of relocation and concentration as the first step in a systematic programme of murder that accelerated through 1942-43 and ended with the liquidation of the Ghetto and the murder of those who had survived this long in Auschwitz and other camps. The district was immortalised in Thomas Keneally\'s book Schindler\'s Ark (1982) and Steven Spielberg\'s film Schindler\'s List (1993), much of which was filmed in Kazimierz and Podgórze. Today the quarter has undergone a remarkable cultural revival: the Old Synagogue (the oldest in Poland, built in the 15th century), the Remuh Synagogue and cemetery, and several other historic synagogues have been restored as active places of worship and museums; the Jewish Culture Festival held each June is one of the largest in the world; and the streets around Szeroka ulica and Plac Nowy have filled with galleries, cafés, klezmer music bars, and restaurants serving traditional Jewish-Polish cuisine alongside the most creative contemporary cooking in the city.',
],
[
'title'       => 'Wieliczka Salt Mine — Underground Cathedral',
'order'       => 4,
'location'    => ['lat' => 49.9838, 'lng' => 20.0542],
'description' => 'Take the short 15-minute train or bus ride southeast of Krakow to the Wieliczka Salt Mine — a UNESCO World Heritage Site since 1978 and one of the most extraordinary underground spaces on earth, a network of tunnels, chambers, and lakes extending 287 kilometres in total and reaching 327 metres below the surface, continuously excavated for salt from the 13th century until 2007. The mine was one of the most important industrial enterprises in medieval and early modern Central Europe: the revenue it generated — from the salt that was then as economically vital as oil is today — funded the construction of Wawel Castle, maintained the Polish army, and made Krakow one of the wealthiest cities in Central Europe for 400 years. The guided tour (the only way to visit) descends through approximately 3 kilometres of passages connecting 20 chambers over three levels, revealing a world that defies expectation at every turn: the miners who spent their lives underground created an entire subterranean culture of art, religion, and storytelling expressed in carved salt. The Chapel of St. Kinga — the mine\'s principal underground church, at 54 metres long and 18 metres wide the largest underground chapel in the world — is almost entirely carved from salt: the walls, the floor, the chandeliers (which glow amber from the crystalline sodium chloride), the altarpieces, the bas-relief images of scenes from the New Testament, and the salt-crystal chandelier hanging from the vaulted ceiling. The chapel took three generations of miner-sculptors nearly 70 years to complete (1895-1963) and has hosted regular Catholic services throughout that time, as well as concerts (the acoustics in salt-rock are exceptional), weddings, and in recent years health tourism stays for respiratory conditions.',
],
[
'title'       => 'Schindler\'s Factory — Memory in the City',
'order'       => 5,
'location'    => ['lat' => 50.0466, 'lng' => 19.9577],
'description' => 'Cross the Vistula River to Podgórze — the district where the Nazis established the Krakow Ghetto in 1941, confining the remaining Jewish population behind walls into an area originally built for a quarter of the number of people now forced to inhabit it — to visit the Oskar Schindler Factory Museum, housed in the original enamelware factory on Lipowa Street where the German industrialist and improbable rescuer employed and thereby saved approximately 1,200 Jewish workers from deportation and death. The story of Schindler — an ethnic German from Czechoslovakia, a member of the Nazi party, initially a war profiteer who saw the occupation as an opportunity for cheap labour and personal enrichment — and his transformation into a genuine rescuer motivated by growing moral awareness of what the Nazi programme actually meant is one of the most complex and remarkable individual stories of the Second World War. Thomas Keneally\'s 1982 novel and Spielberg\'s film, with its devastating final scenes of survivors visiting Schindler\'s grave in Jerusalem, brought the story to global attention; the museum, opened in 2010, places it within the full historical context of the occupation of Krakow and the systematic murder of its Jewish population. The museum\'s permanent exhibition — "Krakow Under Nazi Occupation 1939-1945" — is one of the finest and most thoughtful historical museums in Poland, using the original factory spaces and an innovative combination of objects, documents, photographs, and personal testimonies to convey both the administrative machinery of mass murder and the human reality of individual experience within it. The museum is deliberately demanding: allow two hours and expect to be profoundly affected.',
],
],
];

// ============================================================
// TOUR 6 — ATHENS: The Cradle of Democracy
// ============================================================
$tours[] = [
'title'       => 'Athens: The Acropolis, Democracy & the Western Mind',
'description' => 'Athens is where the West began. In this compact, sun-bleached city at the southern tip of the Balkan Peninsula, surrounded by mountains and facing the Aegean Sea, a small community of around 30,000 free male citizens in the 5th century BC invented democracy, tragedy, philosophy, history, and architectural forms that still define how Western civilisation conceives of government, art, and reason. The Parthenon on the Acropolis — built between 447 and 432 BC as an act of democratic cultural assertion — remains, 2,500 years after its completion, the most influential building ever constructed: its proportions, its formal language, and its civic symbolism have been replicated in the parliaments, banks, museums, and public buildings of every Western democracy from Washington DC to Canberra. Modern Athens is a chaotic, passionate, frequently maddening, and ultimately utterly fascinating city of 3.7 million people — sun-drenched and loud, its ancient marbles rising improbably above the concrete sprawl of the 20th century. The archaeological sites are extraordinary; the food is excellent; and the light — the famous Attic light that Plato described as the medium of truth — is unlike anything else in Europe.',
'duration'    => 195,
'country'     => 'Greece',
'city'        => 'Athens',
'location'    => ['lat' => 37.9838, 'lng' => 23.7275],
'steps'       => [
[
'title'       => 'The Acropolis — The Monument to Democracy',
'order'       => 1,
'location'    => ['lat' => 37.9715, 'lng' => 23.7267],
'description' => 'The Acropolis — literally "the high city" — is the defining monument of Western civilisation and one of the most visited and most significant archaeological sites in the world. A flat-topped limestone outcrop rising 156 metres above the city of Athens, the Acropolis was fortified and inhabited since the Neolithic period (4000-3000 BC), served as the residence of the Mycenaean kings who built the great Bronze Age palaces of the Mediterranean, and was transformed in the 5th century BC under the leadership of Pericles and the vision of the sculptor Pheidias into the greatest concentration of architectural and sculptural achievement in the ancient world. The Parthenon, the temple of Athena Parthenos (Athena the Virgin), was built between 447 and 432 BC entirely in Pentelic marble, its 8 by 17 Doric columns supporting a sculptural programme of extraordinary ambition: 92 metopes depicting the battles of the Olympian gods against the forces of chaos, a continuous frieze of 160 metres depicting the Panathenaic procession (the vast civic-religious festival that united all Athenians in common identity), and two enormous pediment groups narrating the birth of Athena and her contest with Poseidon for patronage of the city. The building has been a temple, a Christian church, and a mosque; was severely damaged by a Venetian bombardment in 1687 (the Ottomans were using it to store gunpowder); and has been under continuous restoration since 1975. The Propylaea — the monumental gateway to the Acropolis, begun in 437 BC and never completed due to the outbreak of the Peloponnesian War — is in some ways the more interesting building: its asymmetrical plan, forced by the sacred boundaries of earlier shrines, produces a spatial sequence of compression and release that Mnesikles, its architect, manipulated with genius.',
],
[
'title'       => 'The Acropolis Museum — Marble in Context',
'order'       => 2,
'location'    => ['lat' => 37.9688, 'lng' => 23.7293],
'description' => 'At the foot of the Acropolis hill, the Acropolis Museum opened in 2009 in a spectacular building designed by the Swiss-American architect Bernard Tschumi specifically to display the surviving sculptures from the Acropolis monuments in the context of the city they came from. The building — glass, concrete, and steel, its top floor rotated 23 degrees to align precisely with the Parthenon visible above through the panoramic windows — is built over an active archaeological excavation of an ancient Athenian neighbourhood from the 1st to 7th century AD, visible through glass floors in the ground level lobby. The museum houses the most significant surviving fragments of the Parthenon\'s sculptural decoration: 50 of the 92 original metopes, 15 of the 17 pediment sculptures, and 80 metres of the original 160-metre frieze. The caryatids from the Erechtheion porch — six female figures serving as columns, five of the originals in the museum and one in the British Museum — are displayed at eye level, allowing viewers to appreciate for the first time the extraordinary individuality of the faces and the quality of the drapery carving. The top floor gallery is arranged in the exact orientation of the Parthenon above, allowing the visitor to understand the spatial relationship between the sculptures and the building they came from. The museum makes the case for the return of the Elgin Marbles — the 17 pediment sculptures and 80 metres of frieze removed by Lord Elgin between 1801 and 1812 and now in the British Museum — more powerfully than any argument alone could: the gaps on the frieze where the Elgin Marbles should be are deliberately left as voids, their absence more eloquent than their presence could be.',
],
[
'title'       => 'The Ancient Agora — Where Democracy Was Born',
'order'       => 3,
'location'    => ['lat' => 37.9754, 'lng' => 23.7219],
'description' => 'Northwest of the Acropolis, the Ancient Agora of Athens was for several centuries the heart of Athenian public life — the marketplace, law courts, council chamber, and social gathering place where democracy was practised in its original, direct form. The word "agora" means both "marketplace" and "assembly" in Greek — a duality that captures the essence of Athenian democratic culture, in which commercial, political, and social life were inseparable. It was here that Socrates conducted his philosophic dialogues — stopping citizens and asking them to define justice, courage, and virtue with the relentless questioning that earned him both the title "the wisest man in Athens" (from the Delphic Oracle) and a death sentence by hemlock in 399 BC. His pupil Plato\'s Academy, where Aristotle in turn studied for 20 years, was established northwest of the city. The best-preserved building in the Agora is the Temple of Hephaestus (Hephaisteion), built around 450 BC and one of the best-preserved Greek temples in the world — its survival is due to its conversion into a Christian church in the 7th century AD, which protected it from the quarrying that destroyed most other ancient buildings. The Stoa of Attalos — a two-storey commercial colonnade built around 150 BC by the King of Pergamon as a gift to Athens — was completely reconstructed in the 1950s using ancient materials and techniques and now houses the Agora Museum, which displays among other objects the ostraka (pottery sherds) used in the Athenian practice of ostracism: citizens voted each year on whether to exile a politician considered dangerous to democracy by scratching his name on a piece of broken pottery.',
],
[
'title'       => 'Monastiraki & Plaka — The Living City Below the Rock',
'order'       => 4,
'location'    => ['lat' => 37.9755, 'lng' => 23.7246],
'description' => 'At the base of the Acropolis, the neighbourhoods of Plaka and Monastiraki form the oldest continuously inhabited part of Athens, a dense maze of neoclassical houses, Byzantine churches, Ottoman mosques, and Roman monuments that represents the full stratigraphic complexity of a city occupied without interruption for 3,500 years. Plaka — the old quarter directly beneath the Acropolis, its streets climbing the northern slope in a grid first established in the Roman period — is the most architecturally coherent neighbourhood in Athens, its 19th-century neoclassical houses painted in the white, yellow, and terracotta of the Greek island aesthetic, their window boxes overflowing with geraniums and bougainvillea. The neighbourhood contains the Tower of the Winds — an extraordinary octagonal marble clocktower built around 50 BC that served simultaneously as a weather vane, sundial, water clock, and compass, its eight faces each carved with a personification of the wind from that direction — and the Roman Forum, built by Julius Caesar and Augustus as a new commercial centre when the Ancient Agora became too crowded. Monastiraki, centred on the square at the intersection of several major streets and named for the small 10th-century monastery (monastiráki — little monastery) that still stands at its centre, is the commercial heart of the area: the flea market on Ifestou Street and the Sunday market spreading through the surrounding streets offer one of the finest concentrations of antiques, vintage clothing, handmade jewellery, second-hand books, and Athens street food in the city. The rooftop bar scene has also transformed the neighbourhood: the view of the Acropolis lit at night from a terrace in Monastiraki, with a glass of raki and a plate of tzatziki, is one of the most satisfying experiences Athens offers.',
],
[
'title'       => 'National Archaeological Museum — Treasures of the Ancient World',
'order'       => 5,
'location'    => ['lat' => 37.9893, 'lng' => 23.7323],
'description' => 'The National Archaeological Museum of Athens is the largest and most important museum of ancient Greek art and culture in the world, housing a collection that spans 7,000 years of human history from the Neolithic period to late antiquity, accumulated through two centuries of excavation across the Greek world. The building, a neoclassical palace begun in 1866 and expanded several times since, is vast — its 8,000 exhibits require at least three hours to do justice to — but the highlights are so extraordinary that no visitor should leave Athens without seeing them. The Mycenaean Gold Collection contains the treasures excavated by Heinrich Schliemann from the shaft graves of Mycenae in 1876, including the gold funeral mask that Schliemann — in a triumph of wishful thinking — immediately attributed to Agamemnon. The mask dates to around 1550-1500 BC; Agamemnon, if he existed, would have lived approximately 300 years later. The mask itself is one of the most powerful objects in human history regardless of its attribution: a portrait of a Bronze Age ruler, beaten gold, its features individualistic and somehow moving — the slightly asymmetric features of a real human face preserved in gold for 3,500 years. The Antikythera Mechanism — recovered from a 2nd-century BC shipwreck off the island of Antikythera in 1901 and still the subject of ongoing research — is a bronze mechanical computer designed to predict astronomical events, eclipse cycles, and the dates of the Olympic Games. It contains at least 37 interlocking gear wheels and represents a level of mechanical sophistication that was not achieved again in Europe until the 14th century; discovering its existence fundamentally changed what we know about ancient Greek technology.',
],
[
'title'       => 'Cape Sounion & the Temple of Poseidon',
'order'       => 6,
'location'    => ['lat' => 37.6528, 'lng' => 24.0267],
'description' => 'Take the coastal bus or hire a car for the 70-kilometre drive south from Athens along the Attic coast to Cape Sounion, where the Temple of Poseidon stands on a cliff 60 metres above the Aegean Sea and offers one of the most magnificent sunset views in the entire Mediterranean world. The cape has been sacred to Poseidon — god of the sea and earthquakes — since at least the Bronze Age; the current temple was built between 444 and 440 BC, almost exactly contemporary with the Parthenon, in the Doric order using the same Agrileza marble. The temple\'s 15 surviving columns (of the original 34) are visible from the sea up to 65 kilometres away, and they guided sailors entering the waters around Attica for centuries — the first sight of the gleaming marble columns on the horizon was the landmark that told Greek sailors they were approaching home. The cape is also where King Aegeus of Athens waited for the return of his son Theseus from Crete, where Theseus had gone to kill the Minotaur. Theseus had promised to change his ship\'s sails from black to white if he survived — but forgot. Seeing the black sails of the returning ship, Aegeus threw himself from the cliff in grief and died, giving the Aegean Sea its name. If you look carefully at column 57 in the second row from the north, you can make out a name carved into the marble: "Byron" — Lord Byron visited Sounion in 1810 and left his signature on the ancient stone with a casual act of vandalism that would cause considerable controversy if attempted today.',
],
],
];

// ============================================================
// TOUR 7 — DUBLIN: Literary Pubs, Viking Origins & the Celtic Soul
// ============================================================
$tours[] = [
'title'       => 'Dublin: Literary Pubs, Viking Streets & the Celtic Soul',
'description' => 'Dublin is one of Europe\'s most characterful and most underestimated capital cities — a place of enormous literary and musical wealth, complex historical identity, and a social warmth generated by the pub culture that is as genuinely distinctive and irreplaceable as any tradition in European urban life. The city was founded by Vikings in 841 AD at a ford on the Liffey River — "Dubh Linn" means Black Pool in Old Irish, referring to a dark tidal pool at the confluence of the Liffey and the Poddle — and grew rapidly as a Norse trading settlement before being captured by the Irish high king Brian Boru in 1014, then by the Anglo-Normans in 1170, beginning a 750-year English colonial relationship that shaped everything about the city: its architecture, its language, its social divisions, and the extraordinary literature of rage, wit, and grief that this collision of cultures produced. In the 20th century alone, Dublin produced Samuel Beckett, James Joyce, William Butler Yeats, George Bernard Shaw, Oscar Wilde, and Bram Stoker — a concentration of literary genius per capita unmatched by any city of comparable size in the world. The pubs in which much of this genius marinated, debated, and occasionally performed are still there, still dispensing the finest Guinness in the world (it genuinely tastes different from the same liquid served elsewhere, a fact attributed variously to the Liffey water, the Dublin air, the skill of Irish barpeople, and the will of God).',
'duration'    => 195,
'country'     => 'Ireland',
'city'        => 'Dublin',
'location'    => ['lat' => 53.3498, 'lng' => -6.2603],
'steps'       => [
[
'title'       => 'Trinity College & the Book of Kells',
'order'       => 1,
'location'    => ['lat' => 53.3439, 'lng' => -6.2546],
'description' => 'Begin at Trinity College Dublin — Ireland\'s oldest and most prestigious university, founded in 1592 by Queen Elizabeth I on the site of an Augustinian priory confiscated during the dissolution of the monasteries — and enter the Old Library to see the Book of Kells, the most celebrated manuscript in the world and a work of such extraordinary artistic ambition and technical virtuosity that scholars and artists have been studying and marvelling at it for 1,200 years without exhausting its complexity. The Book of Kells is an illuminated Gospel manuscript created by Celtic monks around 800 AD, probably on the island of Iona off the Scottish coast, and brought to the monastery of Kells in County Meath following a Viking raid. It is written in Insular majuscule script on 340 calfskin vellum folios, and its 2,000 decorated initials, full-page carpet pages, and figurative illustrations represent the peak of Insular art — the tradition of manuscript illumination developed in Irish and Scottish monasteries between the 6th and 9th centuries that blended Celtic interlace patterns, Christian iconography, and an almost hallucinogenic attention to decorative detail. The Chi-Rho page (folio 34r), the initial page of St. Matthew\'s Gospel, contains forms and designs that can only be distinguished under magnification — suggesting that the monks who created them understood their work to be invisible to human eyes but fully visible to God. The Long Room above the Book of Kells exhibition is one of the most beautiful library spaces in the world: a barrel-vaulted hall 65 metres long, its upper gallery supported by dark oak columns, and its shelves containing 200,000 of the oldest books in the Trinity collection. The smell of old books and warm wood is itself worth the admission.',
],
[
'title'       => 'Kilmainham Gaol — Where Ireland Was Born',
'order'       => 2,
'location'    => ['lat' => 53.3416, 'lng' => -6.3086],
'description' => 'Take the tram or a short taxi west to Kilmainham Gaol, the former prison that served as the site of some of the most important events in Irish history and is today one of the most emotionally powerful museum experiences in Ireland — a place where the physical fabric of the building serves as a direct memorial to the individuals whose suffering within its walls produced the Irish state. The jail was built in 1796 and remained in continuous use until 1924, serving as both a regular prison and the preferred location for the execution of Irish political prisoners by the British authorities. The 1916 Easter Rising — the armed rebellion staged in Dublin over the Easter weekend of 24-30 April 1916 by Irish Republican forces seeking independence from Britain — ended with the unconditional surrender of the insurgents and the execution by firing squad in the prison yard of 14 of the Rising\'s leaders over the following two weeks. The executions — conducted one by one over nine days in conditions of maximum secrecy that the British authorities initially believed would prevent them from becoming martyrs — produced precisely the opposite effect: public opinion in Ireland, initially hostile to the Rising, transformed into broad republican sympathy as the executions continued, eventually producing the political conditions that led to Irish independence in 1922. James Connolly, the socialist leader who was too badly wounded to stand, was tied to a chair for his execution. Robert Emmet, Éamon de Valera, Charles Stewart Parnell, and numerous leaders of the Land League and the Irish Republican Brotherhood were imprisoned here at various times. The guided tour — the only way to visit — is one of the finest interpretive experiences in Ireland, conducted with a directness and emotional intelligence that allows the full weight of this history to be felt without sentimentality.',
],
[
'title'       => 'The Guinness Storehouse — The Black Stuff',
'order'       => 3,
'location'    => ['lat' => 53.3419, 'lng' => -6.2868],
'description' => 'A ten-minute walk from Kilmainham, the Guinness Storehouse at St. James\'s Gate is Ireland\'s most visited tourist attraction and the world\'s most popular brand experience — a self-guided museum of the most famous stout in the world, housed in a magnificent Victorian cast-iron building (originally the fermentation plant of the brewery) that has been transformed into a seven-storey experience culminating in the Gravity Bar, a 360-degree glass-walled bar at the top of the building offering panoramic views over Dublin and a complimentary pint of Guinness. Arthur Guinness signed the lease on the St. James\'s Gate brewery in 1759 — a 9,000-year lease at £45 per year, perhaps the most optimistic commercial transaction in history — and the brewery has been producing stout on the same site continuously ever since, today making approximately 1.5 billion pints per year for export to 150 countries. The stout itself is the product of four ingredients — water, barley, hops, and yeast — plus a proprietary brewing process in which roasted unmalted barley gives the beer its characteristic dark colour and coffee-bitter flavour. The nitrogen carbonation that creates the famous two-part pour and cascading surge was developed by Michael Ash, a Guinness mathematician, in 1959 — an innovation that allowed Guinness to be served on draught without the flat sourness that affected other stouts. The museum\'s brewing galleries, advertising archives (the Guinness poster collection from the 1930s-1970s, designed by artists including John Gilroy, is one of the finest bodies of commercial art from the 20th century), and the Gravity Bar together constitute the best-designed brand experience in Ireland.',
],
[
'title'       => 'Temple Bar & the Literary Pub Crawl',
'order'       => 4,
'location'    => ['lat' => 53.3455, 'lng' => -6.2647],
'description' => 'The Temple Bar Cultural Quarter — a cobblestoned network of streets between Dame Street and the Liffey on the south bank — is Dublin\'s most touristic neighbourhood and, simultaneously, one of the genuinely most culturally alive: the concentration of live music venues, theatres, arts centres, and traditional Irish pubs that makes it exhausting in the summer nights also makes it the most direct access point to the Dublin that produced its extraordinary literary culture. The area takes its name from Sir William Temple, who owned property here in the 17th century, and the "bar" refers to the embankment along the river. The neighbourhood became bohemian in the 20th century when Dublin Corporation considered demolishing it for a bus terminal; artists, musicians, and writers moved into the cheap studios and the city reconsidered. The Dublin Literary Pub Crawl — a guided evening walk through the pubs most closely associated with the city\'s writers — begins from The Duke on Duke Street (where Ulysses characters drink in the "Lestrygonians" episode) and visits a series of establishments where Beckett, Behan, Kavanagh, and their contemporaries drank, argued, and sometimes wrote. The Palace Bar on Fleet Street (est. 1823), with its Victorian interior of mahogany and mirrors, was the unofficial headquarters of the Irish Press literary scene in the 1940s-50s. Mulligan\'s on Poolbeg Street (est. 1782) is generally regarded as having the finest and most carefully maintained Guinness in Dublin. The Long Hall on South Great George\'s Street, with its remarkable Victorian interior of gilded mirrors, dark wood, and hanging clocks, is the most beautiful traditional pub interior in the city.',
],
[
'title'       => 'Chester Beatty Library — The World in Books',
'order'       => 5,
'location'    => ['lat' => 53.3427, 'lng' => -6.2672],
'description' => 'Within Dublin Castle\'s grounds, the Chester Beatty Library has been voted Europe\'s best museum on multiple occasions and is one of the finest collections of manuscripts, rare books, prints, and minor arts in the world — assembled by Alfred Chester Beatty (1875-1968), an American mining engineer and philanthropist who became an Irish citizen in 1957 and donated his entire collection to the Irish state. Beatty spent 50 years acquiring objects of beauty and historical significance from across the world with unusual taste and scholarly rigour: the library contains approximately 22,000 manuscripts, rare books, miniature paintings, prints, drawings, and decorative arts from Islamic, East Asian, European, and other traditions spanning 5,000 years of human civilisation. The Islamic collections are of world significance: the finest early Quran manuscripts outside the Arab world, including examples of 9th-century Kufic calligraphy that represent the art of the written word at its highest development; Persian and Mughal miniature paintings of extraordinary refinement; and Ottoman imperial documents and textiles of remarkable quality. The East Asian collections include some of the finest Japanese woodblock prints (ukiyo-e) in European hands, including works by Hokusai and Hiroshige; Chinese jade books; and Burmese, Siamese, and other Southeast Asian manuscripts on palm leaf and paper. The European collections contain 6 pages of the Book of Kells (on loan from Trinity) and a remarkable collection of biblical papyri dating to the 2nd and 3rd centuries AD. Admission is free, the building is beautiful, and the rooftop garden offers unexpectedly fine views of Dublin Castle and the city.',
],
],
];

// ============================================================
// TOUR 8 — BERLIN: Divided City, Reunited Memory
// ============================================================
$tours[] = [
'title'       => 'Berlin: Wall, Memory & the Reinvention of a Capital',
'description' => 'Berlin is the most historically charged city in Europe and, arguably, the most important. No other city on earth has been so completely at the centre of the defining catastrophes of the 20th century: the First World War ended here in a revolution that toppled the Kaiser and created the doomed Weimar Republic; the rise of Nazism and the implementation of the Holocaust were administered from here; the Second World War was fought to its end on these streets; and for 28 years — from 1961 to 1989 — the city was literally divided by a wall that served as the most visible symbol of the Cold War and the most concrete expression of what totalitarianism means for individual human lives. Since reunification in 1990, Berlin has reinvented itself with remarkable energy and creativity as Germany\'s capital, its cultural capital, and one of the most vital cities in Europe for art, music, architecture, and intellectual life. The city bears its history not as a burden but as a responsibility: the Memorial to the Murdered Jews of Europe, the Topography of Terror, the East Side Gallery, and dozens of memorials, museums, and Stolpersteine (stumbling stones — brass plates in the pavement marking the homes of Holocaust victims) make Berlin\'s engagement with its past the most serious and sustained programme of historical reckoning in the world.',
'duration'    => 210,
'country'     => 'Germany',
'city'        => 'Berlin',
'location'    => ['lat' => 52.5200, 'lng' => 13.4050],
'steps'       => [
[
'title'       => 'Brandenburg Gate & the Memorial to the Murdered Jews of Europe',
'order'       => 1,
'location'    => ['lat' => 52.5163, 'lng' => 13.3777],
'description' => 'Begin at the Brandenburg Gate — the most iconic landmark in Germany and a monument whose history over three centuries encapsulates the full range of German political experience. Built between 1788 and 1791 to designs by Carl Gotthard Langhans in the neoclassical Doric style, inspired by the Propylaea entrance to the Acropolis in Athens, the gate was the triumphant entry point to the royal city of Berlin and its crowning architectural statement of Prussian ambition. Napoleon marched his troops through it in 1806 after defeating Prussia at the Battle of Jena and carried the Quadriga — the bronze chariot of Victory on the summit — to Paris as a trophy; it was returned in 1814 after his defeat. The gate stood in the demilitarised border zone between East and West Berlin from 1961 to 1989, inaccessible from both sides — a closed symbol in the heart of a divided city — until the night of 9 November 1989 when the Wall fell, and crowds from both halves of the city met beneath it for the first time in 28 years in scenes that marked the end of the Cold War. Two minutes\' walk south, the Memorial to the Murdered Jews of Europe — designed by the architect Peter Eisenman and opened in 2005 — occupies 19,000 square metres of land near the former site of Hitler\'s bunker with 2,711 grey concrete stelae of varying heights arranged in a sloping grid. The memorial refuses conventional memorial language — there are no names, no inscriptions, no overt symbols — creating instead a spatial experience of disorientation, isolation, and subtle dread that is one of the most powerful works of contemporary memorial architecture in the world. The information centre beneath contains the individual stories of victims.',
],
[
'title'       => 'Reichstag Building — Democracy Under Glass',
'order'       => 2,
'location'    => ['lat' => 52.5186, 'lng' => 13.3761],
'description' => 'A five-minute walk northwest of the Brandenburg Gate, the Reichstag building — the German Parliament — is one of the most symbolically loaded buildings in Europe and one of the most brilliantly reimagined. The original building was completed in 1894 to house the parliament of the newly unified German Empire, its neo-Renaissance bulk topped by a glass-and-iron dome designed by Paul Wallot. In February 1933, just four weeks after Hitler\'s appointment as chancellor, the building was set on fire under circumstances that have never been conclusively established: the Nazis immediately blamed a young Dutch communist, Marinus van der Lubbe, who was arrested at the scene, tried, and guillotined; historians have never agreed on whether the fire was genuinely set by van der Lubbe, organised by the Nazis as a pretext to suspend civil liberties, or something in between. The fire provided Hitler with the pretext to issue the Reichstag Fire Decree, suspending civil liberties, allowing mass arrests, and effectively ending the Weimar Republic within a month of his appointment. The building was damaged further in the battle for Berlin in 1945, left derelict for decades, and became briefly famous in 1995 when the artists Christo and Jeanne-Claude wrapped it entirely in silver fabric as an art installation viewed by 5 million visitors. The Norman Foster reconstruction (1995-1999) created a new glass dome above the plenary chamber — accessible to the public, free of charge — whose spiralling internal ramp allows visitors to look down into the parliamentary chamber below (the symbolism of citizens being physically above their representatives is deliberate) while the exterior dome reflects sunlight into the chamber. Pre-registration is required for free visits.',
],
[
'title'       => 'East Side Gallery & Checkpoint Charlie',
'order'       => 3,
'location'    => ['lat' => 52.5050, 'lng' => 13.4399],
'description' => 'The Berlin Wall — the Berliner Mauer — was built overnight beginning 13 August 1961 by the East German government (with Soviet backing) to stop the mass emigration of East German citizens to the West that was threatening to depopulate the country. At its maximum extent the Wall was 155 kilometres long, reinforced by a second parallel wall, a "death strip" between them equipped with searchlights, trip wires, guard dog runs, and watchtowers, and patrolled by border guards with orders to shoot to kill. Between 1961 and 1989, at least 140 people are confirmed to have died attempting to cross it; the true number may be considerably higher. The East Side Gallery on the Mühlenstrasse is the longest surviving section of the Wall — 1.3 kilometres of original concrete panels painted in 1990 by 105 artists from 21 countries, creating the world\'s largest open-air gallery, its murals ranging from Dmitri Vrubel\'s famous image of Brezhnev and Honecker kissing (a memory of the socialist fraternal kiss that both men would have preferred to forget) to Birgit Kinder\'s Trabant crashing through the wall. Checkpoint Charlie — "Checkpoint Charlie" was the name used by Western Allied forces for the crossing point at Friedrichstrasse — is a short taxi ride south, accompanied by a small but excellent museum (the Mauermuseum) documenting the extraordinary variety of escape attempts from East to West: in hot air balloons, in modified car engines, in surfboards, in suitcases, through tunnels, and by dozens of other methods of heroic desperation. The recreated checkpoint booth is a tourist cliché but the museum behind it is genuinely moving.',
],
[
'title'       => 'Museum Island — Five Museums on One Island',
'order'       => 4,
'location'    => ['lat' => 52.5195, 'lng' => 13.3988],
'description' => 'In the heart of Berlin, in the Spree River, Museum Island — Museumsinsel — is a UNESCO World Heritage Site containing five world-class museums constructed between 1830 and 1930 that together constitute one of the most extraordinary concentrations of art and antiquities in the world, rivalled only by the Vatican Museums and the Louvre for sheer density of masterworks per square metre. The complex is the result of a Prussian cultural programme of extraordinary ambition: the decision to build public museums accessible to all citizens (rather than private royal collections) made Berlin, from the 1830s onward, one of the great museum cities of Europe. The Pergamon Museum is the most visited museum in Germany for good reason: it contains three complete reconstructed ancient monuments of staggering scale. The Pergamon Altar (180-160 BC), the monumental altar from the ancient city of Pergamon in modern Turkey, stands 18 metres high and 36 metres wide; its frieze of gods battling giants is the largest and finest example of Hellenistic sculpture in existence. The Ishtar Gate of Babylon (575 BC) — the ceremonial entrance to Nebuchadnezzar II\'s city, covered in brilliantly glazed blue and gold tiles bearing the images of dragons and bulls — fills an entire room and is one of the most beautiful objects of ancient Near Eastern art ever excavated. The Market Gate of Miletus (120 AD), a complete Roman city gate transported to Berlin in the early 20th century, demonstrates the scale of Roman civic architecture with sobering directness. The Neues Museum houses Nefertiti — the famous painted limestone portrait bust of the Egyptian queen, carved around 1345 BC, whose serene beauty and extraordinary state of preservation has made it one of the most iconic faces in human history.',
],
[
'title'       => 'Kreuzberg & Street Food at Markthalle Neun',
'order'       => 5,
'location'    => ['lat' => 52.4985, 'lng' => 13.4190],
'description' => 'Complete your Berlin experience in Kreuzberg — the district that has served successively as Berlin\'s working-class Turkish neighbourhood, its punk-and-alternative counterculture heartland, its hipster creative quarter, and is now one of the most culturally diverse and genuinely interesting urban neighbourhoods in Germany, all of these identities still visible in the same streets simultaneously. Kreuzberg was a West Berlin working-class district in the divided city years, pressed against the Wall on three sides and therefore the cheapest real estate in the west — attracting Turkish guest workers from the 1960s onwards and radical students, artists, and musicians who found in its cheap rents and political energy the conditions for a flourishing alternative culture. After reunification, the Wall\'s removal opened Kreuzberg to the east and the neighbourhood expanded in identity and energy; today the area around Bergmannstrasse, Oranienstrasse, and the canal is a mix of Turkish kebab and produce shops, vinyl record stores, independent bookshops, design studios, galleries, and some of the most interesting restaurants in Berlin. Markthalle Neun — Market Hall Nine — at Eisenbahnstrasse 42 is a cast-iron market hall built in 1891 and restored in 2011 as a mixed food market and event space that has become one of the leading examples of the street food and artisan food market revival in Germany. Every Thursday evening the Street Food Thursday market fills the hall with 30-40 vendors offering food from every culinary tradition represented in Berlin\'s extraordinary immigrant population. The Vietnamese, Turkish, Lebanese, Ethiopian, Korean, and Nordic food stalls are consistently excellent; the natural wine selection is remarkable. The weekend market on Saturday mornings focuses on regional and organic produce of exceptional quality.',
],
],
];

// ============================================================
// TOUR 9 — MUNICH: Beer, Baroque & Alpine Beauty
// ============================================================
$tours[] = [
'title'       => 'Munich: Royal Bavaria, Beer Halls & the Alps at the Edge of the City',
'description' => 'Munich — München — is the most liveable large city in Germany and one of the most prosperous and culturally ambitious in Europe: the capital of Bavaria, a kingdom that maintained a fierce independence from the rest of Germany until 1871 and whose royal house — the Wittelsbachs, who ruled for 738 unbroken years from 1180 to 1918 — channelled their wealth and their genuine artistic sensibility into building a city of remarkable Baroque and Neoclassical grandeur. The city is best known internationally for Oktoberfest — the annual beer festival held on the Theresienwiese meadows that has grown from a royal wedding celebration in 1810 to the largest annual public festival in the world, attracting 6-7 million visitors over 16-18 days — but Munich\'s cultural ambitions go far beyond beer: the three Pinakothek museums form the finest art collection in Germany; the Deutsches Museum is the largest science and technology museum in the world; and the English Garden, larger than Central Park, is the finest urban park in Europe. The Alps begin a one-hour drive south of the city centre, and the combination of urban sophistication, royal heritage, beer culture, and immediate access to mountain landscape gives Munich an appeal that its residents exploit with unselfconscious enthusiasm.',
'duration'    => 195,
'country'     => 'Germany',
'city'        => 'Munich',
'location'    => ['lat' => 48.1351, 'lng' => 11.5820],
'steps'       => [
[
'title'       => 'Marienplatz & the Glockenspiel',
'order'       => 1,
'location'    => ['lat' => 48.1374, 'lng' => 11.5755],
'description' => 'Begin at Marienplatz — the central square of Munich and the heart of the city since its foundation by Henry the Lion, Duke of Bavaria and Saxony, in 1158 — a spacious, pedestrianised square dominated by the twin towers of the New Town Hall (Neues Rathaus) and animated by one of the most famous carillon spectacles in Germany. The Marienplatz takes its name from the Mariensäule — the column of the Virgin Mary, erected in 1638 to give thanks for Munich\'s survival of the plague and the Thirty Years\' War — which stands at the centre of the square and has served as the city\'s symbolic zero point ever since. The New Town Hall — despite its name and Gothic appearance, actually built between 1867 and 1908 — is a massive neo-Gothic building in Belgian Gothic style whose 85-metre tower houses the famous Glockenspiel, a carillon of 43 bells accompanied by 32 life-size mechanical figures that perform daily at 11am, 12pm, and (in summer) 5pm. The performance depicts two episodes from Munich\'s history: the wedding of Duke Wilhelm V of Bavaria in 1568, when richly costumed knights joust and the court dances; and the 1517 "Dance of the Coopers" performed by the city\'s barrel makers after the Black Death to show the healthy citizens that life in Munich was worth living. The Old Town Hall at the eastern end of the square, a genuine Gothic building from the 15th century (rebuilt after wartime damage), now houses a toy museum. The pedestrian zone spreading from Marienplatz — the Kaufingerstrasse and Neuhauser Strasse — is the busiest shopping street in Germany, but the medieval street plan, the 14th-century St. Peter\'s Church (the oldest church in Munich, whose tower offers the finest view of the city), and the covered market alleys behind the square reward those who look beyond the retail.',
],
[
'title'       => 'Viktualienmarkt — Munich\'s Daily Food Theatre',
'order'       => 2,
'location'    => ['lat' => 48.1348, 'lng' => 11.5762],
'description' => 'A two-minute walk south of Marienplatz, the Viktualienmarkt is Munich\'s most beloved institution and one of the finest daily food markets in Europe — an open-air food market occupying the same site continuously since 1807, where over 140 stalls offer the finest produce of Bavaria and beyond in an atmosphere that manages to be simultaneously a functioning market, a social club, a tourist attraction, and the daily shopping ground of Munich\'s most food-conscious residents. The market was established by King Max I Joseph when the original market in Marienplatz became too crowded; "Viktualien" is an old German word for food provisions, reflecting its origin as a wholesale produce market. Today the stalls specialise in what Munich does best: exceptional charcuterie (the Weisswurst — the white veal sausage made fresh each morning and traditionally eaten before noon, with sweet mustard and a pretzel, and never accompanied by a knife, only by the Zuzeln technique of sucking the meat from the skin — is the Viktualienmarkt\'s most iconic product); extraordinary cheese, including local Allgäu varieties and international selections; wild mushrooms and seasonal vegetables from Bavarian farms; freshly baked Brezen (pretzels) of a quality unavailable outside Bavaria; and honey, jams, herbs, and flowers in extraordinary variety. The central Biergarten — one of the most atmospheric in Munich, with tall chestnut trees and blue-and-white checked tablecloths — serves cold Maß (one-litre tankards) of draught beer from a different Munich brewery every week on a rotating schedule, a democratic tradition maintained since the 1960s to ensure no single brewery monopolises the most prominent beer garden in the city.',
],
[
'title'       => 'Alte Pinakothek — Six Centuries of European Masters',
'order'       => 3,
'location'    => ['lat' => 48.1490, 'lng' => 11.5699],
'description' => 'The Alte Pinakothek — Old Picture Gallery — is one of the oldest art museums in the world and one of the great collections of European painting, housing over 700 masterworks from the 14th to 18th centuries assembled by the Wittelsbach kings of Bavaria over four centuries of passionate collecting. The building, designed by Leo von Klenze and opened in 1836, was severely damaged in the Second World War and partly rebuilt in the 1950s — the patched bomb-damaged sections of the exterior are deliberately left visible, a characteristic Munich decision to make the evidence of history legible rather than concealing it. The collection\'s German section is the finest in the world: Albrecht Dürer\'s Four Apostles (1526), his largest and most theologically significant work, and his Self-Portrait of 1500 — the most discussed self-portrait in art history, in which Dürer presents himself in a Christ-like frontal pose that simultaneously claims artistic genius as a form of divine gift and asserts the painter\'s full intellectual and spiritual equality with his subjects — are the undisputed high points. Matthias Grünewald\'s Christ on the Cross and Hans Holbein\'s portraits of the European court are equally essential. The Flemish and Dutch holdings are extraordinary: Rubens represented in depth and at scale (his Rape of the Daughters of Leucippus and the massive Last Judgement are overwhelming); Van Dyck, Rembrandt, and Van Eyck at their finest. The Italian collection includes Raphael\'s Holy Family (the Canigiani Madonna), three major works by Titian, and Leonardo da Vinci\'s Madonna of the Carnation, one of his earliest surviving works and a painting whose exhibition anywhere in the world would be a major event.',
],
[
'title'       => 'English Garden — The World\'s Greatest Urban Park',
'order'       => 4,
'location'    => ['lat' => 48.1642, 'lng' => 11.6050],
'description' => 'The Englischer Garten — the English Garden — is the largest urban park in the world, at 3.7 square kilometres considerably larger than both Central Park in New York and Hyde Park in London, and is used by Munich\'s residents with an intensity and democratic ease that makes it the most genuinely public space in the city. The park was designed from 1789 onwards by the American-born British officer Count Rumford (Sir Benjamin Thompson), at the request of Prince Karl Theodor of Bavaria, in the "English landscaped garden" style that had been revolutionising European aristocratic garden design since the mid-18th century: informal, naturalistic, with meadows, woodland, streams, and lakes replacing the geometric formality of the French Baroque tradition. Its democratic intention was explicit from the beginning — Rumford designed it as a public pleasure ground for all citizens, not a private royal garden — and Munich\'s residents have responded by using every square metre of it with joyful promiscuity. The most famous feature is the Eisbach wave: a standing wave on a small artificial channel near the southern entrance where surfers — real surfers, on real surfboards — have been riding a perpetual 1-2 metre wave in the middle of a city park since the 1970s. The sight of technically accomplished surfers performing nose rides and tube manoeuvres on a grey Munich afternoon, with cyclists and joggers passing by without a second glance, is one of the most distinctively Munich experiences available. Beer gardens throughout the park — most famously the Chinese Tower beer garden, the largest in Munich with seating for 7,000, and the Seehaus on the Kleinhesseloher See — serve cold Maß in all weathers.',
],
[
'title'       => 'Hofbräuhaus & Bavarian Beer Culture',
'order'       => 5,
'location'    => ['lat' => 48.1378, 'lng' => 11.5798],
'description' => 'A short walk from Marienplatz, the Hofbräuhaus am Platzl is the most famous beer hall in the world and one of the most visited tourist attractions in Germany — a state-owned brewery and beer hall founded in 1589 by Duke Wilhelm V of Bavaria (the same Duke whose wedding is commemorated in the Glockenspiel) to supply the Bavarian court with its preferred dark beer, later opened to the public and transformed into the cultural institution it has been since 1828. The main hall on the ground floor seats 1,300 people at long communal tables, served by Bedienungen (waitresses) in traditional Dirndl dress carrying several Maß tankards simultaneously with practised ease while an oompah band plays on the stage. The beer — the Hofbräu Oktoberfest, the HB Original, and the seasonal Maibock — is brewed to standards set by the Reinheitsgebot, the Bavarian Beer Purity Law of 1516, which remains the oldest food regulation still in force in the world and stipulates that beer may be brewed using only water, malt, and hops. Munich\'s brewing culture is older and more serious than its Oktoberfest reputation suggests: the city has been brewing beer continuously since at least the 9th century (monastic records from 1040), and today hosts six major breweries — Augustiner, Paulaner, Hacker-Pschorr, Spatenbräu, Löwenbräu, and Hofbräu — that together supply the city and the world with approximately 100 million litres of beer per year. The Hofbräuhaus also has a darker historical footnote: it was in this building that Hitler gave his first major public speech in 1920 and announced the 25-point platform of the National Socialist German Workers\' Party.',
],
],
];

// ============================================================
// TOUR 10 — SEVILLE: Flamenco, Mudéjar Splendour & the Guadalquivir
// ============================================================
$tours[] = [
'title'       => 'Seville: Flamenco, Mudéjar Splendour & the Gateway to the New World',
'description' => 'Seville is the most sensually magnificent city in Spain and the capital of Andalusia — a city of extraordinary architectural beauty, passionate music, and a historical identity formed at the intersection of three cultures: the Roman who called it Hispalis, the Moorish who named it Isbiliya and made it one of the great cities of medieval Europe, and the Christian who conquered it in 1248 and from whose ports Christopher Columbus departed for the Americas in 1492, making Seville for over a century the richest city in the Western world as the gateway of the Spanish empire. The extraordinary Alcázar palace complex — still a royal residence, the oldest continuously occupied palace in Europe — the enormous Gothic Cathedral with its Moorish bell tower and Columbus\'s tomb, and the ornate María Luisa Park with its 1929 World\'s Fair pavilions are all UNESCO World Heritage sites and represent the full sweep of Sevillian architectural ambition. But the true character of the city is felt most strongly in its barrios — in the Triana neighbourhood across the Guadalquivir where flamenco was born, in the Santa Cruz labyrinth of the former Jewish quarter, and in the tapas bars along the Alameda de Hércules where the evening begins at 10pm and ends sometime the following morning.',
'duration'    => 195,
'country'     => 'Spain',
'city'        => 'Seville',
'location'    => ['lat' => 37.3891, 'lng' => -5.9845],
'steps'       => [
[
'title'       => 'Seville Cathedral & La Giralda',
'order'       => 1,
'location'    => ['lat' => 37.3858, 'lng' => -5.9930],
'description' => 'The Catedral de Santa María de la Sede — Seville Cathedral — is the largest Gothic cathedral in the world and, after St. Peter\'s in Rome and St. Paul\'s in London, the largest church building in the world by volume. It was built between 1401 and 1528 on the site of the former Great Mosque of Seville — the mosque built by the Almohad dynasty in the late 12th century and considered one of the finest in the Islamic world — incorporating the mosque\'s minaret and courtyard while demolishing the prayer hall. The scale of the undertaking is suggested by the minutes of the chapter meeting that authorised the project in 1401: "Let us build a church so large that those who see it finished will think we were mad." They were not wrong: the cathedral is 126 metres long, 83 metres wide, and 30 metres to the vaulted ceiling, its five naves creating an interior of overwhelming and somewhat vertiginous scale. The high altar retablo — the altarpiece, completed in 1564 — is the largest altarpiece in the world, 27 metres high and 18 metres wide, containing 45 carved scenes from the lives of Christ and the Virgin executed in gilded timber over four generations by successive master craftsmen. The tomb of Christopher Columbus, carried by four allegorical kings representing the kingdoms of Castile, León, Navarra, and Aragon, stands in the south transept — his remains were brought here from Havana in 1898. The Giralda, the former minaret of the mosque, stands 93 metres tall and is the symbol of Seville: its Almohad brickwork, its Renaissance bell chamber added in 1568, and the bronze weathervane on top (Giraldillo — the small Giralda, a female figure representing Faith) are visible across the city. It is climbed not by stairs but by 35 ramps designed for the imam\'s horse.',
],
[
'title'       => 'Real Alcázar — The Palace of Three Civilisations',
'order'       => 2,
'location'    => ['lat' => 37.3836, 'lng' => -5.9904],
'description' => 'Adjacent to the cathedral, the Real Alcázar de Sevilla is the oldest royal palace still in active use in Europe — Spanish kings and queens continue to use it as their official Seville residence — and one of the most beautiful buildings on earth, a palace complex of extraordinary layered splendour that represents the most complete expression of Mudéjar art anywhere in Spain. The Mudéjar style — the architectural tradition in which Christian patrons employed Muslim craftsmen working in Islamic decorative techniques after the Christian reconquest — produced its finest work here: the intricate geometric tilework (azulejos), the carved plasterwork (yesería) in infinite arabesque patterns, the wooden stalactite ceilings (artesanado) of the main rooms, the courtyard fountains and water channels that cool the palace through the hot Seville summer — all are the work of craftsmen from the former Nasrid Kingdom of Granada working for Christian kings who correctly identified Islamic architectural culture as the most sophisticated in the Iberian Peninsula. The Patio de las Doncellas — the Courtyard of the Maidens — is the heart of the palace, a rectangular courtyard with a central pool reflecting the arched galleries and plasterwork panels above, built for King Pedro I between 1356 and 1366; it is one of the most photographed courtyard spaces in the world. The extensive gardens behind the palace — a sequence of terraced Renaissance and Baroque garden rooms descending from the palace walls — are among the most beautiful in Spain and provide welcome cool shade during the Seville summer.',
],
[
'title'       => 'Barrio Santa Cruz — The Labyrinth of the Old Jewish Quarter',
'order'       => 3,
'location'    => ['lat' => 37.3870, 'lng' => -5.9890],
'description' => 'Immediately east of the Alcázar, the Barrio Santa Cruz occupies the site of the medieval Jewish quarter of Seville — one of the most significant Jewish communities in medieval Iberia, home to physicians, scholars, and financial advisors to the Castilian court before the pogroms of 1391 killed much of the community and the Alhambra Decree of 1492 expelled the survivors along with all other Jews from Spain. The barrio is a labyrinth of narrow white-walled alleys, unexpected plazas, orange trees, and hidden patios — the street pattern deliberately tortuous both for defensive purposes and to create shade in a city where summer temperatures exceed 40°C. The characteristic white-washed walls (encalado, renewed each year), the wrought-iron window grilles (rejas), the ceramic flower pots mounted on every available surface, and the sound of flamenco guitar drifting from a bar that is invisible until you turn the next corner are the defining sensory experiences of the quarter. The Plaza de Doña Elvira — a small square with a central fountain and benches shaded by orange trees — is one of the most intimate and beautiful public spaces in Seville. The Casa de Murillo, at the square\'s edge, was the home of Bartolomé Esteban Murillo, the greatest Sevillian painter of the 17th century, whose tender images of street children and Immaculate Conceptions made him the most popular artist in Spain and, for a period in the 18th century, the most valuable painter in the world (his work fetching higher prices at auction than Raphael or Titian). The Hospital de los Venerables Sacerdotes (now a cultural foundation) contains the finest Murillo collection in Seville.',
],
[
'title'       => 'Triana — The Cradle of Flamenco',
'order'       => 4,
'location'    => ['lat' => 37.3786, 'lng' => -6.0030],
'description' => 'Cross the Guadalquivir River via the Isabel II Bridge (popularly known as the Triana Bridge) into the neighbourhood of Triana — the most legendary barrio in Seville and the neighbourhood most closely associated with the origin and continuing vitality of flamenco, the art form that emerged in Andalusia in the late 18th and early 19th centuries from the confluence of Romani (Gitano), Moorish, Jewish, and Andalusian folk musical traditions and became one of the most powerful, complex, and emotionally immediate forms of musical expression in the world. Triana has been a working-class Romani neighbourhood for at least 500 years, its streets between the river and the Calle Betis forming the epicentre of a flamenco culture that produced the majority of the most important cantaores (singers), bailaores (dancers), and guitarists of the 19th and early 20th centuries: La Niña de los Peines, Pastora Pavón — considered by many the greatest flamenco singer of all time — was born here; Manuel Torre and Manolo Caracol, the two singers who defined the cante jondo (deep song) tradition, were Trianeros. The neighbourhood also has a ceramic tradition stretching back to the Moorish period: the famous Triana azulejo workshops that produced the tiles for the Alcázar and the buildings of the 1929 World\'s Fair are still working; Cerámica Santa Ana on Calle San Jorge, established in 1870, is the oldest ceramics factory in Seville. The bars along Calle Betis on the riverside are the best in Seville for a pre-dinner glass of fino sherry and a plate of jamón — the river view of the Torre del Oro and the cathedral at sunset is the quintessential Seville experience.',
],
[
'title'       => 'Plaza de España & María Luisa Park',
'order'       => 5,
'location'    => ['lat' => 37.3773, 'lng' => -5.9868],
'description' => 'A fifteen-minute walk south of the cathedral, the Plaza de España and the adjacent María Luisa Park represent the most spectacular expression of early 20th-century Spanish civic ambition and are among the most visually impressive public spaces in the country. The Plaza de España was built as the centrepiece pavilion of the Ibero-American Exposition of 1929 — a World\'s Fair designed to demonstrate the vitality and cultural achievement of Spain and its former colonies and to attract international investment — to designs by Aníbal González in a Regionalist architectural style that blends Renaissance and Baroque elements with Moorish detailing in a way that celebrates Andalusian architectural tradition while updating it for the 20th century. The result is a vast semicircular building 200 metres in diameter, its two 80-metre towers flanking an arcaded façade of warm brick and ceramic tile that curves around a central plaza with a canal crossed by four bridges. The most remarkable feature is the series of 48 ceramic tile benches arranged around the base of the arcade, each representing one of Spain\'s provinces with a decorated azulejo scene of its history and geography — a miniature tile encyclopedia of Spanish geography that tourists sit on to be photographed with equal enthusiasm to that with which locals use them to eat their lunch. The building has served as a film location for Lawrence of Arabia (1962) and Star Wars: Attack of the Clones (2002). The surrounding María Luisa Park — 340,000 square metres of gardens, fountains, and tree-lined promenades donated to the city by the Infanta Luisa Fernanda in 1893 — is the finest public park in southern Spain.',
],
],
];

// ============================================================
// TOUR 11 — PORTO: Azulejos, Port Wine & the Douro at Dusk
