'steps'       => [
[
'title'       => 'São Bento Station — The Azulejo Cathedral',
'order'       => 1,
'location'    => ['lat' => 41.1460, 'lng' => -8.6109],
'description' => 'Begin at the most beautiful railway station in the world: the Estação de São Bento, Porto\'s central train station, whose main hall is entirely covered in 20,000 blue-and-white azulejo tiles depicting scenes of Portuguese history, daily life, and landscape in one of the most ambitious and successful programmes of architectural tile decoration ever executed. The station was built between 1900 and 1916 on the site of a 16th-century Benedictine convent (São Bento — Saint Benedict — gives the station its name) to designs by the architect José Luís Monteiro, who specified that the interior should be decorated entirely in azulejos as a demonstration of the highest achievement of Portuguese decorative arts. The tile panels were designed by Jorge Colaço and executed between 1905 and 1916, depicting on the north wall a panoramic history of Portugal in transport and combat: medieval battle scenes, royal entries into cities, and the arrival of John I at Porto in 1387 for his marriage to Philippa of Lancaster; on the lateral walls, scenes of rural life in different regions of Portugal — harvesting grapes in the Douro, fishing on the Atlantic coast, making wine in the Alentejo — executed with a documentary precision and an emotional warmth that makes them among the finest works of Portuguese art of the 20th century. The station is, above all, still fully functioning — trains depart regularly for the Douro Valley wine country, the beaches north of Porto, and Lisbon. Taking a day trip to the Douro Valley on the regional train, its tracks running alongside the river through steeply terraced vineyards, is one of the most beautiful train journeys in Europe.',
],
[
'title'       => 'Livraria Lello — The Most Beautiful Bookshop in the World',
'order'       => 2,
'location'    => ['lat' => 41.1476, 'lng' => -8.6149],
'description' => 'A ten-minute walk uphill from São Bento, the Livraria Lello at Rua das Carmelitas 144 has been described by virtually every architecture and travel writer who has visited it as the most beautiful bookshop in the world — and the description is not hyperbole. Founded in 1906 by the brothers José and António Lello, the shop occupies a neo-Gothic building designed by Francisco Xavier Esteves with a façade of red and grey carved stone that would not look out of place on a Venetian palace, a stained glass skylight filtering jewelled light into the interior below, and a central double staircase in carved dark wood that curves upward in a spiral of extraordinary elegance and has been photographed several million times. The interior is two floors of dark oak shelving packed with books, the upper floor reached via the famous staircase through a gallery lined with columns and painted with murals depicting Progress and Art. The shop was for decades the meeting place of Porto\'s intellectual and literary life; J.K. Rowling, who lived in Porto between 1991 and 1993 teaching English, was a regular visitor and has acknowledged that the staircase influenced the staircase at Hogwarts. Today the shop charges a small entrance fee (redeemable against purchases) to control the crowds that would otherwise make functioning as a bookshop impossible. The selection of Portuguese and international literature is excellent; the art books section, on the upper floor, is one of the finest in Portugal. Buy something, if only to contribute to the continued existence of one of the great institutions of European literary culture.',
],
[
'title'       => 'Church of São Francisco — Gothic Gold',
'order'       => 3,
'location'    => ['lat' => 41.1403, 'lng' => -8.6170],
'description' => 'The Igreja de São Francisco — the Church of Saint Francis — is the most extraordinary interior in Porto and one of the most overwhelming Gothic-Baroque spaces in Portugal: a 14th-century Gothic church that was transformed in the 17th and 18th centuries by the application of approximately 400 kilograms of gold to every available surface, producing an interior of such gilded excess that it has been described as simultaneously the most beautiful and the most disturbing room in Portugal. The church was built between 1383 and 1410 as the church of the Franciscan friary — the Order of Friars Minor, founded by St. Francis of Assisi on the principle of absolute poverty, which makes the golden interior of their church in Porto one of the more piquant ironies in religious architecture. The nave is entirely Gothic: pointed arches, ribbed vaults, and tall windows creating a vertical soaring space of great dignity. But every surface of that Gothic space is covered in baroque carved and gilded lime wood (talha dourada) — the altarpieces, pilasters, capitals, cornices, and even the columns are entirely encrusted in carved wood gilded with Brazilian gold that the Portuguese empire was extracting from Minas Gerais in extraordinary quantities during the 17th and 18th centuries. The effect is of standing inside a golden forest: every surface animated by cherubs, saints, grapes, flowers, columns, and canopies in a riotous celebration of imperial wealth and Catholic devotion that strikes every visitor differently. Beneath the church, the ossuário (ossuary) containing the bones of generations of Porto\'s dead — layered in the earth beneath the flagstones — can be visited and provides a memorable note of mortality beneath all that golden opulence.',
],
[
'title'       => 'Ribeira & the Douro Riverfront',
'order'       => 4,
'location'    => ['lat' => 41.1408, 'lng' => -8.6143],
'description' => 'Walk down from the Church of São Francisco to the Ribeira — Porto\'s medieval riverfront neighbourhood, a UNESCO World Heritage Site, and the most photographed face of the city: a tightly packed row of medieval houses four to six stories tall, their facades a chaotic patchwork of azulejo tiles, bare stone, painted plaster, and laundry, rising directly from the Cais da Ribeira (Ribeira Quay) that lines the northern bank of the Douro. The Ribeira was the commercial heart of medieval Porto, its wharves loading and unloading the goods that flowed through the city — wine from the Douro Valley, fish from the Atlantic, textiles from northern Europe — and it retains its commercial energy today in the restaurants and bars that fill the ground floors of every building and spill out across the quay in summer. The flat-bottomed wooden boats moored along the quay — the barcos rabelos, historically used to transport barrels of port wine down the Douro from the Douro Valley — are now pleasure craft, but their presence creates the most picturesque maritime scene in the city. Cross the lower deck of the Dom Luís I Bridge — the iron double-decker bridge designed by Théophile Seyrig (a disciple of Gustave Eiffel) and opened in 1886, whose upper deck connects the historic centres of Porto and Vila Nova de Gaia 60 metres above the river — to the south bank and the port wine lodges. The view from the bridge itself, upstream and downstream, is the definitive Porto panorama.',
],
[
'title'       => 'Vila Nova de Gaia — The Port Wine Lodges',
'order'       => 5,
'location'    => ['lat' => 41.1360, 'lng' => -8.6120],
'description' => 'Cross the Douro to Vila Nova de Gaia on the south bank — technically a separate municipality but inseparable from Porto in cultural and commercial identity — where the port wine lodges line the riverfront in a continuous row of painted stone buildings whose company names (Graham\'s, Taylor\'s, Sandeman, Ferreira, Ramos Pinto) are among the most recognised brand names in the wine world. Port wine — the fortified wine produced in the Douro Valley approximately 100 kilometres upstream — has been aged and exported from these lodges since the early 18th century, when British merchants established the trade routes and the commercial relationships that have given many of the most famous port houses their English and Scottish names. The wine is produced from grapes grown on the steeply terraced schist slopes of the Douro Valley in three sub-regions — Cima Corgo, Baixo Corgo, and Douro Superior — under conditions of extreme heat and poor soil that stress the vines into producing concentrated, intensely flavoured fruit. The most prestigious ports — Vintage, Late Bottled Vintage (LBV), Colheita, and aged Tawny — can be aged in the lodges for anywhere from 10 to 40 years before release, developing complexity, dried fruit flavours, and a particular nuttiness (in Tawny styles) that makes mature port one of the most rewarding wine experiences in the world. Most lodges offer guided tours and tasting experiences; Quinta do Crasto, Graham\'s, and Ramos Pinto are among the finest. A Tawny 10-year with a plate of presunto (air-dried ham) and a view of the Dom Luís bridge at sunset is an experience of uncomplicated pleasure that Porto offers with generous ease.',
],
],
];

// ============================================================
// TOUR 12 — STOCKHOLM: Vikings, Design & the Archipelago
// ============================================================
$tours[] = [
'title'       => 'Stockholm: Vikings, Scandinavian Design & the Archipelago Capital',
'description' => 'Stockholm is arguably the most beautiful capital city in northern Europe — a metropolitan centre built across 14 islands at the point where Lake Mälaren meets the Baltic Sea, its waters, bridges, and green spaces giving it an openness and clarity that larger Continental capitals lack. Founded in the 13th century as a trading post controlling the vital waterway between the Baltic and the Swedish interior, Stockholm became the capital of the Swedish Empire in the 17th century when Sweden was briefly one of the great powers of Europe, and the city was endowed with the royal palaces, churches, and aristocratic townhouses that still define its historical core. Sweden\'s particular contribution to world culture — the design philosophy that insists on beauty, functionality, and democratic access to good design simultaneously — is visible everywhere in the city, from the furniture and interiors of the 17th-century houses of Gamla Stan (the Old Town) to the iconic products of IKEA, Volvo, and the extraordinary tradition of Swedish graphic design. The city\'s museums are exceptional: the Vasa Museum, housing a complete 17th-century warship raised from the harbour in 1961, is the most visited museum in Scandinavia; the ABBA Museum and the Nobel Museum reflect the city\'s dual cultural personality of pop phenomenon and intellectual seriousness. Beyond the city, the Stockholm archipelago — 30,000 islands, islets, and rocks stretching 80 kilometres into the Baltic — is one of the great natural environments of northern Europe.',
'duration'    => 195,
