[
'title'       => 'Gamla Stan — The Old Town on an Island',
'order'       => 1,
'location'    => ['lat' => 59.3250, 'lng' => 18.0710],
'description' => 'Gamla Stan — the Old Town — is Stockholm\'s original island settlement and one of the best-preserved medieval city centres in Europe, a compact network of narrow cobblestone streets, coloured medieval buildings, and quiet squares that has been continuously inhabited since the 13th century. The island of Stadsholmen (the Town Island) sits at the centre of Stockholm where the freshwater of Lake Mälaren meets the salt water of the Baltic, and the original town established here in 1252 by Birger Jarl grew rapidly into the commercial and political capital of medieval Sweden. Walking through Gamla Stan today along its three main medieval streets — Stora Nygatan, Lilla Nygatan, and the Prästgatan, the Priest Street — past buildings painted in the characteristic Swedish palette of deep red, ochre, yellow, and grey, with their steep copper roofs and the occasional medieval round tower, feels genuinely like stepping into the 17th century. The narrowest street in Stockholm — Mårten Trotzigs Gränd, barely 90 centimetres at its tightest point — has been threading between buildings since the 16th century. Stortorget — the Great Square — at the centre of the old town was the site of the Stockholm Bloodbath in November 1520, when the Danish King Christian II invited the Swedish nobility and clergy to a feast in the Royal Castle, then arrested them and executed over 90 people in three days in an attempt to end the Swedish independence movement. The brutality of the Bloodbath had the opposite effect: Gustavus Vasa used it as a rallying point for a successful revolt that expelled the Danes permanently and established Sweden as an independent kingdom in 1523. The German Church (Tyska kyrkan) on Stortorget was the church of Stockholm\'s powerful German merchant community and is still conducting services in German.',
],
[
'title'       => 'Vasa Museum — The Warship That Sank on Its Maiden Voyage',
'order'       => 2,
'location'    => ['lat' => 59.3281, 'lng' => 18.0913],
'description' => 'On the island of Djurgården, the Vasa Museum houses the most complete surviving 17th-century ship in the world and offers one of the most overwhelming museum experiences in Scandinavia — standing beneath a complete, intact warship built in 1628 that sank on its maiden voyage in Stockholm harbour and was raised from the seabed 333 years later in an extraordinary feat of underwater archaeology. The Vasa was the most powerful warship in the Swedish navy when it launched on 10 August 1628 — a massive, heavily armed galleon 69 metres long, carrying 64 bronze cannon on two gun decks, its stern castle decorated with hundreds of carved and painted wooden sculptures of gods, warriors, and symbolic figures constituting the most elaborate programme of ship decoration ever documented. The ship sailed approximately 1,300 metres before a gust of wind heeled it onto its port side, water poured through the open gun ports, and the Vasa sank in 32 metres of water, killing approximately 30 of the 150 people on board. The cold, oxygen-poor waters of the Baltic preserved the ship in extraordinary condition: when the marine archaeologist Anders Franzén located the wreck in 1956 and it was raised in 1961, 95% of the original hull timbers were intact and 14,000 carved wooden fragments — the remains of the decorative programme — were recovered from the seabed. The museum was purpose-built around the ship, which is displayed on five levels allowing visitors to examine every detail from the keel to the tip of the bowsprit and the remarkable sculptural programme at close range. The reason for the sinking — the ship was too top-heavy, with too many cannon for its beam — was understood at the time and apparently reported to the Swedish king, who chose to ignore the advice.',
],
[
'title'       => 'The Royal Palace & Changing of the Guard',
'order'       => 3,
'location'    => ['lat' => 59.3268, 'lng' => 18.0715],
'description' => 'The Royal Palace — Kungliga Slottet — on the north side of Gamla Stan is the official residence of the Swedish Royal Family and the largest royal palace in the world still used as an official royal residence, with 1,430 rooms across its seven floors of Baroque and Rococo architecture. The current palace was designed by Nicodemus Tessin the Younger following a catastrophic fire that destroyed the medieval Three Crowns Castle in 1697, and construction continued under four monarchs over 60 years, the building finally completed in 1760. Despite its imposing exterior — a massive, austere Baroque block of pale grey stone designed in the Italian Baroque style by an architect who had studied in Rome and Paris — the interior is one of the finest examples of Rococo decorative arts in Scandinavia, its state rooms preserving largely intact the furnishings, tapestries, and decorative objects accumulated by Swedish monarchs over 250 years. The Hall of State houses the Silver Throne (1650) on which Swedish monarchs were crowned until 1907 and the opening of parliament is still conducted; the Bernadotte Apartments display the state rooms used for official receptions; the Royal Chapel maintains an active liturgical function. The Royal Armoury (Livrustkammaren) in the palace basement — one of the oldest museums in the world, founded in 1628 — contains the coronation regalia, royal carriages, and personal possessions of Swedish monarchs from the 16th century to the present, including the bloodstained uniform of Gustavus Adolphus, Sweden\'s greatest warrior king, who wore it at the Battle of Lützen in 1632. The Changing of the Guard ceremony in the outer courtyard takes place daily in summer and is one of the most precisely choreographed military ceremonies in Scandinavia.',
],
[
'title'       => 'Fotografiska — The World\'s Leading Photography Museum',
'order'       => 4,
'location'    => ['lat' => 59.3178, 'lng' => 18.0862],
'description' => 'On the Södermalm waterfront overlooking the inner harbour, Fotografiska has established itself since its opening in 2010 as one of the most important photography institutions in the world — a combination of exhibition space, educational programme, restaurant, and cultural hub that has hosted major retrospectives of virtually every significant photographer working today in a converted turn-of-the-century Art Nouveau brick building of considerable architectural distinction. The programming philosophy is deliberately populist in the best sense: major solo shows of photographers working across the full spectrum from photojournalism (Steve McCurry, James Nachtwey) to fine art photography (Annie Leibovitz, Cindy Sherman), fashion (David LaChapelle, Miles Aldridge), and documentary work are designed to bring audiences who would not typically visit a contemporary art gallery into contact with the full breadth of what photography can do and be. The building\'s top-floor restaurant — with panoramic windows overlooking the Djurgården and the spires of Gamla Stan — is among the finest views in Stockholm and serves Nordic cuisine of high quality that has made it a destination in its own right. Fotografiska has since opened spaces in New York, London, Berlin, and Tallinn, but the Stockholm original retains the energy and intimacy of a genuinely grassroots cultural project that happened to become internationally influential. The museum shop is the finest photography bookshop in Scandinavia.',
],
[
'title'       => 'Archipelago Day Trip — 30,000 Islands Await',
'order'       => 5,
'location'    => ['lat' => 59.3410, 'lng' => 18.1715],
'description' => 'No visit to Stockholm is complete without a journey into the archipelago — the extraordinary fragmented landscape of 30,000 islands, islets, skerries, and bare rocks that stretches from the city\'s eastern edge 80 kilometres into the Baltic Sea, inhabited by a combination of year-round farmers and fishermen and summer residents who collectively make the archipelago one of the most intensely lived seasonal landscapes in northern Europe. The Stockholm archipelago is divided into three zones: the inner archipelago, characterised by larger, forested islands and connected to the mainland by bridges; the middle archipelago, where the islands are smaller and more scattered and the summer cottages of Stockholm families crowd every available shore; and the outer archipelago, where the islands flatten and the rock is bare and wind-polished and the light on the water in long summer evenings achieves the particular luminosity that Swedish artists from Carl Larsson onwards have been attempting to capture in paint. Boats leave from Strömkajen quay near the Grand Hotel throughout the day for destinations across the archipelago: the most accessible and rewarding day trip is to Vaxholm — the historic fortress island that controlled shipping into Stockholm from the 16th century, 40 minutes by boat — or Sandhamn, the sailing hub at the outermost edge of the middle archipelago where summer Stockholm congregates on warm August evenings. Swimming in the Baltic in July-August, diving from the rocks of a deserted skerry into clear cold water, and eating a lunch of fresh Baltic herring (strömming) on an outdoor terrace while the archipelago boats pass — these are experiences that embody the Swedish relationship with nature, light, and the sea that defines the country\'s self-understanding more completely than any museum could.',
],
],
];

// ============================================================
// TOUR 13 — COPENHAGEN: Design, Hygge & the World's Best Food City
// ============================================================
$tours[] = [
