'description' => 'Copenhagen is the most liveable capital city in Europe and, in the last two decades, one of the most influential: its extraordinary restaurant culture — centred on the New Nordic Kitchen movement pioneered by René Redzepi at Noma, which changed how the entire world thinks about food — its design tradition of democratic functionalism and elegant simplicity, and its urban planning philosophy of cycling infrastructure and human-scale city-making have made it the model that cities from Melbourne to Madrid aspire to emulate. The Danish capital sits at the edge of the Øresund strait, connected to Sweden by the famous bridge completed in 2000, and its combination of medieval towers, Baroque palaces, contemporary architecture, and the dense network of waterways and canals that thread through the old city creates a visual character of northern elegance that is entirely distinctive. The concept of hygge — that untranslatable Danish word denoting a quality of cosiness, conviviality, and the pleasure of simple things shared with people you trust — is not a marketing concept but a genuine social practice visible in the candle-lit interiors of the city\'s cafés, the communal tables of its food markets, and the astonishing ease with which Copenhageners navigate the public space of their city by bicycle.',
'duration'    => 195,
'country'     => 'Denmark',
'city'        => 'Copenhagen',
