'description' => 'Begin at Nyhavn — the New Harbour — the most iconic and most photographed image of Copenhagen: a 17th-century canal lined on both sides with the brightly painted gabled townhouses of merchants and shipowners, their reflections trembling in the dark water alongside the restored wooden sailing ships moored along the quays. The canal was dug between 1671 and 1673 on the orders of King Frederick III to connect the city centre to the harbour, and the houses that line it were built immediately after by the merchants and sea captains who needed easy access to the new waterway. Despite its current tourist-café-and-restaurant character, the north side of Nyhavn retained its working-class sailor tavern character well into the 20th century — the concentration of tattoo parlours that gave Hans Christian Andersen, who lived in three different houses in the street between 1835 and 1875, his enduring fascination with the street and its inhabitants. Numbers 20, 67, and 18 all claim to have been Andersen\'s residences at various points. The south side of the canal — the sunny side, looking north — is lined with restaurants and café terraces that fill with Copenhageners at every opportunity the weather permits, which in the Danish understanding of what constitutes acceptable outdoor dining temperature includes conditions that most Mediterranean visitors would regard as requiring an overcoat. The quay walls and the restaurant frontages are the most photographed stretch of any city in Scandinavia. For the best view and the most authentic experience, arrive early — before 9am the canal belongs to the joggers and the boats being readied for the day.',
],
[
'title'       => 'Rosenborg Castle & the Crown Jewels',
'order'       => 2,
'location'    => ['lat' => 55.6855, 'lng' => 12.5771],
'description' => 'A fifteen-minute walk from Nyhavn through the streets of the old city, Rosenborg Castle rises unexpectedly from the heart of the King\'s Garden — the oldest royal garden in Denmark — as a compact Dutch Renaissance fantasy of red brick, copper spires, and moat that looks as if it has been miniaturised from a larger prototype, its intimate scale creating an immediacy and charm that larger, grander palaces entirely lack. The castle was built between 1606 and 1634 as a summer residence for King Christian IV — the most ambitious builder in Danish history, who also designed the Round Tower, the Exchange Building, and the Nyboder naval barracks — in the Dutch Renaissance style that dominated northern European architecture in the early 17th century, its spires and decorative elements clearly related to the canal houses of Amsterdam and the town halls of the northern Netherlands. The interior is a remarkable time capsule: unlike most Scandinavian royal palaces, Rosenborg was never modernised and its rooms preserve their original furnishings, tapestries, decorative objects, and artworks from the 17th through early 18th centuries in a condition of extraordinary completeness. The Long Hall on the second floor, used for royal receptions and coronation banquets, is covered in Flemish tapestries depicting King Christian IV\'s naval victories and contains the original ivory and silver throne. The basement treasury houses the Danish Crown Jewels: the Crown of Christian IV (1596), one of the most exquisitely worked pieces of Renaissance goldsmithing in northern Europe; the Ruby Set of Queen Sophie Magdalene; and the Oldenburg Horn, a 15th-century gold drinking vessel that is the oldest piece of Danish royal regalia. The King\'s Garden surrounding the castle is the oldest and most popular public park in Copenhagen.',
],
[
'title'       => 'Designmuseum Danmark — The Art of Everyday Life',
