'location'    => ['lat' => 55.6866, 'lng' => 12.5953],
'description' => 'Danish design — the tradition that produced the chairs of Arne Jacobsen, Hans Wegner, and Finn Juhl, the lamps of Poul Henningsen, the tableware of Royal Copenhagen, and the architectural details of Jørn Utzon (designer of the Sydney Opera House) — is one of the most influential and most beloved design traditions in the world, and the Designmuseum Danmark, housed in a magnificent Rococo building that was formerly the Royal Frederik\'s Hospital (1757), provides the finest introduction to it. The museum\'s permanent collection traces the development of Danish design from the guild crafts of the 18th century through the Arts and Crafts movement, the functionalist revolution of the early 20th century, and the mid-century modern furniture masterpieces that made Danish design globally famous, to the contemporary work of designers operating from Copenhagen today. The key insight that the museum conveys — and that is the core of the Danish design philosophy — is that the distinction between art and craft, between the fine and the applied arts, is a false hierarchy: a well-designed chair that supports the body correctly, is made of beautiful materials, and will last 100 years is a greater cultural achievement than a mediocre painting. Poul Henningsen\'s analysis of the glare problems of early electric lighting, which led him to develop the PH lamp series (1926 onwards) — in which multiple overlapping shades prevent the bulb from being directly visible from any angle while maximising the diffusion of warm light — is presented as the design manifesto it is: a combination of technical problem-solving and aesthetic sensitivity that produced an object so well resolved it is still in production and still the standard by which all table lamps are judged.',
],
[
'title'       => 'Torvehallerne — The New Nordic Market',
