'location'    => ['lat' => 55.6830, 'lng' => 12.5657],
'description' => 'Copenhagen\'s food culture — which has produced more Michelin stars per capita than any other city in the world in the last 15 years, with Noma and Geranium being among the most globally influential restaurants of the 21st century — is accessible in microcosm at Torvehallerne, the glass-and-steel covered market hall on Israels Plads that opened in 2011 and immediately became the food hub of the city. The market consists of two parallel glass halls and an outdoor market area housing approximately 60 vendors of produce, street food, and specialty ingredients, organised to support both the city\'s professional food culture (wholesale produce vendors supply Copenhagen\'s top restaurants) and everyday shopping for quality food. The produce is organised around the New Nordic Kitchen\'s founding principles: locality (most produce from Denmark and the Nordic countries), seasonality (the market changes radically between winter and summer), and quality over quantity. The coffee culture here is exceptional — Copenhagen is one of the finest coffee cities in Europe, with a concentration of specialty roasters (Coffee Collective, The Coffee Collective, Ønsk) that rival any city on the continent. The smørrebrød stands — serving open-faced sandwiches of rye bread piled with pickled herring, smoked salmon, roast beef with remoulade, liver pâté with bacon, or combinations of vegetables and herbs from the New Nordic tradition — are a mandatory stop: smørrebrød is Denmark\'s greatest contribution to the world of lunch. The outdoor market on Friday and Saturday mornings, spreading across Israels Plads with additional vendors of plants, flowers, vegetables, cheese, and street food, draws half of Copenhagen\'s food-conscious population.',
],
[
