'order'       => 5,
'location'    => ['lat' => 55.6739, 'lng' => 12.6000],
'description' => 'A twenty-minute walk or bicycle ride from the city centre, Freetown Christiania occupies 34 hectares of a former military barracks on Christianshavn island and has been one of the most sustained and most discussed urban social experiments in the world since its founding in 1971, when a group of squatters and hippies occupied the abandoned barracks and declared an autonomous territory operating outside the normal laws of Denmark. The founding manifesto declared that the goal was "to build a self-governing society whereby each and every individual holds themselves responsible over the well-being of the entire community." Christiania has approximately 900 permanent residents, its own system of communal governance by consensus, its own economy, its own newspaper, and its own rules (no hard drugs, no weapons, no cars on the main street, no photographs on Pusher Street, where cannabis is openly sold in a arrangement of complex legal ambiguity). The community has survived numerous Danish government attempts to dismantle it — including a constitutional compromise in 2011 that allowed residents to purchase their land at below-market rates — and continues to function as a genuine alternative community that has also become a major tourist attraction. The architecture is extraordinary in its variety and creativity: self-built homes of every conceivable material and style, from timber longhouses to hobbit-hole earthworks, from converted warehouses to purpose-built modernist structures, all expressing the individual personality of their builders within the collective framework. The café and music venue culture is excellent; Loppen is one of the finest small music venues in Copenhagen for live jazz and rock.',
