'description' => 'A short walk from the Markt through the narrow Breidelstraat, the Burg Square was the political heart of medieval Bruges — the site of the Count of Flanders\'s fortress (now demolished), the Town Hall (Stadhuis), the Cathedral of Saint Donatian (also demolished in 1799 by Napoleon\'s forces, who used the stone as building material), and the extraordinary Basilica of the Holy Blood. The Bruges Town Hall, built between 1376 and 1421, is one of the earliest Gothic town halls in the Low Countries and a building of great architectural distinction: its façade, restored in the 19th century, is divided into vertical bays by carved stone piers, each topped by pinnacles with niches for statues of the counts and countesses of Flanders. The interior Gothic Hall is painted with historical scenes from the city\'s medieval history by Albrecht and Jan de Vriendt (1895-1900) and preserves the wooden fan-vaulted ceiling of the original 14th-century room. The Basilica of the Holy Blood, in the southeast corner of the square, is built on two levels: a Romanesque lower chapel of extraordinary sombre beauty (built around 1150 for the Count of Flanders\'s court chaplain) and an upper Gothic chapel rebuilt in the 16th century. The basilica is named for its most prized relic: a phial said to contain drops of the blood of Jesus Christ, brought to Bruges from the Holy Land in 1150 by Count Thierry of Alsace following the Second Crusade. The relic — a small crystal bottle set in a golden reliquary of medieval workmanship — is displayed for veneration each Friday and at the city\'s most important ceremony, the Procession of the Holy Blood, held each year on Ascension Day when the relic is carried through the streets of Bruges in a procession of Biblical characters and medieval guilds watched by 30,000 spectators.',
