'description' => 'The Groeningemuseum is one of the finest collections of Flemish and Belgian painting in the world, housing the most important concentration of Flemish Primitive paintings outside the major national collections — the works produced by the extraordinary school of painters who worked in Bruges and Ghent in the 15th century and revolutionised European painting through their development of oil paint technique, atmospheric perspective, and minute naturalistic detail. Jan van Eyck — generally considered the greatest technical innovator in the history of painting, the person who perfected (and possibly invented) the use of oil as a paint medium, unlocking possibilities of depth, luminosity, and textural detail that tempera painting could never achieve — is represented by the Virgin and Child with Canon van der Paele (1436), one of the most technically accomplished paintings in existence: the armour of the kneeling knight is rendered in such detail that modern art historians can identify the exact workshop that made it; the carpet beneath the throne contains a pattern of Arabic script that Van Eyck had clearly studied from an actual specimen; and the light entering the painted space from windows to the left creates shadows and reflections that obey the laws of optics with a precision that was not improved upon for 400 years. Hans Memling\'s Moreel Triptych (1484) and Gerard David\'s Judgement of Cambyses (1498) — a gruesome depiction of a corrupt judge being flayed alive, ordered by Bruges city council to hang in the court of justice as a warning to their own judges — are among the most significant Flemish paintings of the second half of the 15th century. The museum also holds important works from the Flemish Baroque (Rubens, Van Dyck) and Belgian Symbolist and Surrealist periods, including works by James Ensor and René Magritte.',
